<HEADLINE> U.S. Soon Publishes Rules for Sales of Food to Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The United States is nearing
the fulfilment of rules that govern the sale of food and
medicine to Iran, Sudan and Libya, U.S. Agriculture Department
said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We're getting pretty close," Chris Goldthwait, general sales
manager at the department, said, noting that there were only one
or two details that need to be finalized.
</P>
<P>
"That should be worked out in the next few days," he said.
</P>
<P>
The State Department said the rules should come out by the
end of the month.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Department officials estimate that the easing
of sanctions on Iran, Libya and Sudan could boost U.S. wheat and
corn exports by up to one million tons each annually. Of the
three countries, Iran is considered to have the biggest
potential. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
