<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000 GMT, June 25 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Eight Lebanese were killed and at least 60 others
wounded overnight in the largest Israeli air raids on Lebanon
since 1996.
</P>
<P>
About six Lebanese, most of them civil defense workers, were
killed and 60 others were wounded by Israeli raid on the power
station in Gumhur, 10 kilometers east of Beirut and near the
official residence of President Emile Lahoud and Lebanon's Defense
Ministry and two bridges on the coastal highway linking the
country's southern city of Sidon and
Beirut. (BC-Lebanon-Israel-Raids)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli government has warned that it would
take further action against Lebanon if Beirut fails to curb
Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks on Israeli northern
areas.
</P>
<P>
"If there is not quiet in the north, there woould not be quiet
in Lebanon," the office of outgoing Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu said in a statement after an emergency cabinet meeting
late Thursday night, in which the ministers approved the most
heavy air strike on Lebanon in three years. (BC-Israel-Lebanon)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Following tense negotiations, Israeli Prime
Minister-elect Ehud Barak signed the first coalition agreements
with two political parties on Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement signed with Yisrael Baaliya Party,
which got six Knesset (parliament) seats in the May elections,
the party's leader Natan Sharansky will take up the post as
interior minister in the incoming coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Barak also signed an agreement with National Religious Party
(NRP), which won five seats in Knesset.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, NRP leader Yitzhak Levy will be named as
construction minister while the party's No.2, Shaul Yahalom, as
deputy education minister. (BC-Israel-Politics)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanese President Emile Lahoud said Friday his
country would sue Israel before the International Court of Justice
(ICJ) and claim compensations for the damage resulting from
Israel's air strikes against Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud said at an emergency cabinet meeting that his country
would not bow to the Israeli aggression and would confront it with
the weapon of unity and the resistance option.
(BC-Lebanon-Israel-Raids)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Arab League on Friday demanded an immediate end to
the Israeli "heinous aggression" on Lebanon and its "repression
policy."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the latest Israeli air raid on Lebanese civilian
targets, Arab League Assistant Secretary-General Ahmed Ben Hulai
accused Israel of violating and challenging international law by
attacking civilian facilities in Lebanon.
(BC-Arab League-Lebanon-Israel) 
</P>
</TEXT>
