<HEADLINE> Zanzibar Expects Bumper Harvest of Cloves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Zanzibar is expecting a
bumper cloves harvest of 10,000 tons this year amid the rising of
local production prices, Minister for Trade, Industries and
Marketing Khamis Mussa said in Zanzibar Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mussa told the House of Representatives that preparations by
the government to buy all the cloves have been well underway,
including opening a purchase center in every village especially in
Pemba where the spice is mainly grown.
</P>
<P>
Preparations also included availability of picking tools such
as mats, ropes, hurricane lamps and gunny bags.
</P>
<P>
"We are now just awaiting for the picking season to begin next
month," Mussa said, adding that the government has planned to
borrow loans from the People's Bank of Zanzibar to buy the spice
from growers.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, the producer prices were raised to encourage
the growers to pick the spice.
</P>
<P>
A kilogram of first grade cloves will be 450 Tanzanian
shillings (one U. S. dollar equals some 710 shillings) up from 320
shillings.
</P>
<P>
Despite suffering low prices in the world market, the cloves
remain the prime cash crop accounting for more than 44 percent of
the islands' gross domestic product (GDP). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
