<HEADLINE> U.N. Urges Unremitting War against Drug Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 25 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
said on Friday that the war against drug abuse and illicit
trafficking "is far from won".
</P>
<P>
In his message on the occasion of the International Day
against Drug Abuse and Illicit Trafficking which falls on June 26,
he said the United Nations is the most suitable instrument for
waging this war.
</P>
<P>
This is because of the global implications and cross-border
nature of the scourge, he said.
</P>
<P>
Although tangible progress has been made in the fight, with
demand and supply of dangerous drugs markedly reduced, the fact
remains that between 3 and 4 percent of the world's population
still regularly consumes illegal substances, he said.
</P>
<P>
Intravenous drug use is still one the leading causes of the
spread of AIDS, with devastating consequences across the globe,
and the consumption of some new drugs is increasingly widespread,
especially among young people, he added.
</P>
<P>
Criminal organizations are also taking advantage of
globalization and technological advances in transport and
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Drugs continue "to destroy far too many human lives" and the
U.N. will continue to join global forces to put an end to the
calamity of drug abuse, said Annan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
