<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana Stresses Preventive Education on Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Ghanaian government pays much
attention to the preventive education on drugs, the official Ghana
News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
"There should be a consistent drug preventive education in all
spheres of our lives aimed at educating, in particular, parents,
law enforcement personnel and the youth on the harmful effects and
dangers inherent in drug abuse," Ghanaian Education Minister Ekwow
Spio-Garbrah was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the remarks at a function marking the 13th
International Day Against Drug Abuse and Illicit Trafficking in
Accra Friday.
</P>
<P>
Spio-Garbrah said if the legal, social and economic problems
are well- explained and advice on alternatives to drugs are given
to the youth who are predominant users, they would be careful of
drug dealers who would want to entice them into drugs.
</P>
<P>
"That knowledge would also equip them with skills to identify
drug dealers and drug dealing as destructive nation-wrecking evils
and to expose drug dealing and drug dealers in society," he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the future of any nation depends on the youth
but the pressures of modern life have exposed them to ravages with
an attendant lack of parental control.
</P>
<P>
He also called on Ghanaian musicians, songwriters and producers
to incorporate anti-drug information in their lyrics and
promotional messages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
