<HEADLINE> Ethio-Eritrean War Resumes After One-Week Lull </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Fighting between Ethiopia and
Eritrea resumed at the Mereb-Setit front Friday after a one-week
lull in hostilities.
</P>
<P>
The two Horn of Africa neighbors accused each other of
initiating offensive and both claimed to have an upper hand over
the other during the last round of fighting from June 9 to June
17.
</P>
<P>
The Eritrean Foreign Ministry said in Asmara that Ethiopia
Friday morning opened a new attack on the right flank of the
Mereb-Setit front.
</P>
<P>
The ministry noted in its press release that its forces killed
or wounded more than 18,000 Ethiopian soldiers during the
week-long fighting and also destroyed four Mig-23 fighter planes
and a Mi-35 helicopter gunship.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Office of the Ethiopian Government Spokesperson
said in Addis Ababa that the Eritrean army initiated an offensive
at the Mereb River "once again" Friday.
</P>
<P>
The office noted in its press release that the Ethiopian troops
had put 24,450 Eritrean soldiers out of action in the border
battles one week ago.
</P>
<P>
War between Ethiopia and Eritrea broke out in early May 1998
along their 1,000-kilometer border.
</P>
<P>
Although both countries have agreed to the peace framework put
forward by the Organization of African Unity (OAU), there is in
sight no immediate resolution to the 13-month conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
