<HEADLINE> Britain to Resume Relation With Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON,June 25 (Xinhua) -- Britain announced on Friday that it
had decided to send its ambassador back to Sudan and to resume
normal relations with the African country.
</P>
<P>
"We are pleased to announce that we have agreed to the return
of British and Sudanese staff to (the capital city of Sudan)
Khartoum and London, to carry out the work necessary for a full
normalization of relations," the Foreign Office said in a
statement which had been agreed on by Britain and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
"The resumption of normal relations opens a new page of better
understanding on global and bilateral issues, which will be built
on mutual interest, co-operation and respect," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Britain announced a temporary withdrawal of all UK-based staff
from Khartoum last August in response to the Sudanese demand,
after Britain supported the United States bombing of a medicine
factory in Khartoum.
</P>
<P>
U.S. alleged the Sudanese factory was a base for the exiled
Saudi dissident Osama bin Laden, who was blamed by Washington for
two deadly 1998 embassy bombings in Africa.
</P>
<P>
British staff will return to the Embassy in Sudan in stages, a
foreign office spokeswoman told Xinhua. 
</P>
</TEXT>
