<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon to Ask Israel to Compensate for Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese government is expected to
take legal measures to ask for Israeli compensation for the huge
losses inflicted on Lebanon's infrastructure in the Israeli
biggest air blitz on the country since 1996.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Information Minister Anwar Khalil made the
announcement Friday following an emergency cabinet meeting under
Lebanese President Emile Lahoud.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held hours after Israel launched the bloodiest
offensive on Lebanon since the 1996 "Grapes of Wrath" which killed
at least 240 Lebanese, most of whom are civilians.
</P>
<P>
During the air blitz from Thursday night till Friday dawn,
Israeli warplanes hammered Lebanon's power stations,
telecommunication center and road networks in Beirut, eastern and
southern Lebanese areas.
</P>
<P>
A total of eight Lebanese, most of them civil defense workers,
were killed and 64 others wounded in the attacks.
</P>
<P>
"President Lahoud ordered ministers concerned to speed up the
repair of damaged infrastructure and let it to be open soon
for residents," Khalil said.
</P>
<P>
He added Lahoud also asked the government to take legal
measures to demand compensation from Israel for the huge losses
caused by its attacks.
</P>
<P>
The destruction of Jamhour and Bsaleem power plants, both
on a hill overlooking Beirut, plunged many residential
neighborhoods of Beirut and Lebanon's central mountain into
total darkness at the moment.
</P>
<P>
At present, power is being rationed for the capital and
its environs at a six-in-six-out hourly rate.
</P>
<P>
Three bridges linking Beirut and Lebanon's southern biggest
port city of Sidon were also destroyed in the blast.
</P>
<P>
Initial reports by Lebanon's state-run electricity company said
the Israeli latest blast caused at least 30 million U.S. dollars
in losses.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese government is going to file complaints with the
April Understanding Monitoring Group against Israeli aggression on
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The group, comprising representatives from the U.S., France,
Syria, Israel and Lebanon, was established to monitor the
implementation of a U.S.-brokered cease-fire agreement reached
between Lebanon and Israel after the 1996 Israeli blitz.
</P>
<P>
The deal bars any attacks on civilians or from civilian areas
on both sides of the border.
</P>
<P>
Israel claimed its strike on Lebanon's infrastructure came in
response to Hezbollah's rocket attacks on northern Israel Thursday
night, killing two Israelis and wounding 12 others.
</P>
<P>
But, Hezbollah said in return that its cross-border bombing
served as retaliation for the wounding of six Lebanese civilians
by Israeli forces in the past five days.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been fighting
on a daily basis in a bid to oust Israeli forces and its
proxy South Lebanon Army out of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
