<HEADLINE> Lebanon to Sue Israel Over Air Raids: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Emile Lahoud
said Friday his country would sue Israel before the International
Court of Justice (ICJ) and claim compensations for the damage
resulting from Israel's air strikes against Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud said at an emergency cabinet meeting that his country
would not bow to the Israeli aggression and would confront it with
the weapon of unity and the resistance option.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud asked the cabinet ministers to speed up the revamp works
of power facilities, bridges and roads that were hit by the
Israeli attacks which began late Thursday and ran into the early
hours of Friday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Prime Minister Salim Hoss told the cabinet that
Israel was once again showing its savagery and the mask of
moderation of the new leadership fell along with the hopes for the
resumption of peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak had pledged to withdraw
its troops from south Lebanon within one year during his May
election campaign.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon will stand firm and stick to its rights and dignity as
well as the unity between the Lebanese and the Syrian tracks of
talks with Israel, Hoss said.
</P>
<P>
Information Minister Anwar Khalil said that Lebanon had told
its ambassadors in Washington and New York to brief the United
States and the United Nations Security Council on the Israeli
aggression.
</P>
<P>
Asked about Lahoud's refusal to raise the issue to the
U.N. Security Council, Khalil said Lebanon would not seek a
Security Council resolution as it had already had the resolution
No. 425 that was in no need of revision.
</P>
<P>
On the possibility of resorting to "the April understanding
committee" in dealing with such a largest scale aggression since
1996, Khalil said the committee was the best available means to
Lebanon at present to deal with the issue.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon would stick to the committee despite the Israeli
attempts to undermine it, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese guerrilla group Hezbollah, or Party of God, and
Israel reached an understanding in April 1996 after an Israeli
16-day onslaught on Lebanon in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-brokered agreement bars any attacks on civilians or
from civilian area on both sides of the border.
</P>
<P>
As for the possibility of stopping the Israeli attacks, he said
Lebanon was fully aware that there were no limits to the attacks,
which were claimed to be launched by Israel in response to the
cross-border rocket attacks earlier by the Iranian-backed
Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here from Israel said the decision to launch
the recent attacks was made by outgoing Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak was
informed of its ten minutes after the air raids in operation.
</P>
<P>
Khalil said his government had contacted some friendly nations
to expedite the repair works and received confirmation from Syrian
Minister of Electricity Munib Saem al-Dahr that all the potentials
of his country were at Lebanon's disposal.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah has been fighting to oust Israeli forces and its proxy
South Lebanon Army out of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
