<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Defends Decision on Air Strike against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Outgoing Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu Friday defended his decision to order the
broadest Israeli air strike against Lebanon since 1996, saying
the government should do everything to protect the people in
Israel's northern areas.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot accept the situation where rockets were launched
in our territories without response," he said in a statement
while visiting the northern border town of Kiryat Shimona,
target of waves of Katyusha attacks from Lebanon late Thursday
night in which two civilians were killed.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to see a speedy return to quiet in both
sides, but we should do everything necessary in order to
protect the people here," he was quoted by Israel Radio as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Kiryat Shimona was in atmosphere of tense quiet Friday
afternoon. Residents remained in underground bomb shelters 24
hours after they were first instructed to enter there following
the first wave of Katyusha rocket attacks launched by Hezbollah
guerrillas of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The rockets were fired after Israeli shelling wounded a
Lebanese civilian in a Lebanese village outside the
Israeli-occupied border zone in south Lebanon Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
In response, Netanyahu ordered the heaviest military offensive
in Lebanon since the "Grapes of Wrath" operations in 1996.
Israeli fighter planes struck power stations, bridges and other
civilian targets, some near Beirut, killing 10 and injuring more
than 60.
</P>
<P>
After making the decision to unleash the retaliatory strike,
Netanyahu warned that Hezbollah is mistaken if it thinks it
can take advantage of the period of government transition to
hit residents of the north.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu retains full power until his successor Ehud Barak,
who dealt Netanyahu a landslide defeat in the May elections,
puts together a governing coalition.
</P>
<P>
Barak immediately distanced himself from the decision on the
Israeli air strike. His office made it clear late Thursday
night that he was informed of the decision only after it had
been carried out.
</P>
<P>
His aides said the former army chief was angry over Netanyahu's
decision to hit Lebanese civilian targets in retaliation for
Hezbollah operations, according to Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah is leading a war of attrition to oust Israel soldiers
and its local militia South Lebanon Army from a 15-km-deep border
zone in south Lebanon Israel has occupied since 1985.
</P>
<P>
Barak has pledged to withdraw Israeli troops from Lebanon
within a year of office through negotiations with Syria, the
main power-broker in Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
