<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Parliament Approves Passage of NATO Troops Through Territory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Bulgarian parliament adopted a
resolution on permitting NATO troops to Kosovo passing its
territory within the framework of Operation Joint Guardian.
</P>
<P>
The document was backed by 208 of the 213 Members of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
The resolution specifies that NATO personnel should be under
the obligation to comply with the Bulgarian legislation, guarantee
a safe passage, avoid disturbing the normal civilian traffic and
amend any direct or indirect damage caused by their passage.
</P>
<P>
NATO aircraft and ships will pay no port, airport, navigation
service and other charges. NATO vehicles using the national road
network will be exempt from tolls just like the Bulgarian armed
forces.
</P>
<P>
The articles does not apply to troops of countries that are not
NATO members.
</P>
<P>
Ivan Gloushkov, MP from the Union of Democratic Forces (UDF)
said the resolution is Bulgaria's contribution to the
establishment of peace and stability in Southeastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
But Stefan Gaitandjiev, who against the presence of foreign
troops in the country - both of NATO and Russia, claimed that it
could fail to guarantee the security of the country by allowing
foreign troops passage and stay for an indefinite period of time.
</P>
</TEXT>
