<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British, Irish PMs in N.Ireland to Save Peace Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- British and Irish Prime Ministers
Tony Blair and Bertie Ahern arrived in Belfast for talks on Friday
to break the stalemate on the Northern Ireland peace deal before
next Wednesday's "make-or-brake" deadline.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving for Belfast, Blair said he wanted an early
promise from the Irish Republican Army (IRA) and its political
wing Sinn Fein to decommission all their weapons by May 2000,
according to a Reuters report.
</P>
<P>
Blair's spokesman told reporters in London that the British
prime minister wanted a "yes" to two fundamental questions in his
meetings with David Trimble and Gerry Adams, the key Ulster
Unionist and Sinn Fein negotiators in the dispute over guerrilla
arms which has blocked formation of a devolved government.
</P>
<P>
"Are you committed to an inclusive executive? And are you
committed to decommissioning by May 2000? Those are the two
questions," the spokesman quoted Blair as asking.
</P>
<P>
Trimble's Protestant Ulster Unionist Party has already said it
is ready in principle to include Adams' Sinn Fein in an all-party
executive, one of the key planks of the April 1998 Good Friday
Agreement, providing disarmament takes place. Leading a 30-strong
delegation to the Belfast talks, Trimble said he was committed to
securing peace.
</P>
<P>
"I really do take exception to anyone doubting our willingness
to work with other people, provided they are committed to peace
and democracy, and that is the critical question," he told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein vice-president Pat Doherty told reporters that he
remained hopeful that the Good Friday Agreement would not
flounder, calling it "the route map which can bring us forward."
</P>
<P>
But Blair's insistence on a "yes" to disarmament by next year
will pose serious problems for Sinn Fein, which has always said it
cannot deliver an IRA weapons handover.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister warned in an article in The Times on Friday
that the parties were "staring into the abyss" with less than a
week to go before a deadline for rescuing last year's peace deal.
</P>
<P>
He made clear he expected Sinn Fein and the IRA to come up with
"deeds not words" on decommissioning, but he was prepared to be
flexible over timing between now and May 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
