<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Parliament Approves Building of Holocaust Memorial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The German parliament approved a vote
to build a national memorial in the center of Berlin to remember
six million Jews murdered in the Holocaust under the Nazi Third
Reich.
</P>
<P>
The monument, designed by U.S. architect Peter Eisenman,
envisages a maze of four soccer pitches (fields) filled with 2,700
concrete pillars.
</P>
<P>
German deputies insisted, however, on putting their own mark on
the monument and stipulated the original Eisenman design be
extended with the installation of interpretative texts on the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
"The state itself cannot remember but with symbols it can help
society to remember," said German Culture Minister Michael Naumann
in a speech to the Bundestag, or lower house.
</P>
<P>
"This memorial in the center of our capital is a symbol of our
mourning. It is a part of our history. Above all, it symbolizes
memory... of the murder of millions of people. Today in parliament
we kneel in front of the victims...," declared Naumann.
</P>
<P>
The president of Germany's parliament, Wolfgang Thierse, said
the monument would help allow Germans to end the century with
dignity.
</P>
<P>
Gregor Gysi, the leader of the Party of Democratic Socialism,
said the Holocaust memorial was needed as an answer to rising neo-
Nazi sentiment among youths.
</P>
<P>
Members of parliament had to choose between two designs for the
monument which will be built on a site the size of two football
fields south of the Brandenburg Gate and near the bunker where
Nazi leader Adolf Hitler committed suicide in 1945.
</P>
<P>
A private initiative for the memorial was set up in 1989. This
was taken on by the German federal government in 1992, which
launched a design competition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
