<HEADLINE> Britain Closes Four African Embassies Temporarily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Britain declared on Friday that it
has decided to close its diplomatic missions in four African
countries because of security reasons.
</P>
<P>
"We have information of a possible threat to diplomatic
missions in Gambia, Madagascar, Namibia and Senegal. We...have
taken the precautionary measure of temporarily closing our
missions in these countries," a Foreign Office spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the United States announced on Thursday
that its embassies in Gambia, Liberia, Togo, Madagascar, Namibia
and Senegal would be shut until Sunday because of security
concerns.
</P>
<P>
American embassies have been regarded as especially vigilant
after U.S. intelligence officials revealed that exiled Saudi
dissident Osama bin Laden and his followers, blamed by Washington
for two deadly 1998 embassy bombings in Africa, may be close to
launching another attack.
</P>
<P>
But the British spokesman declined to elaborate on the threat
British embassies would face. He also refused to say where the
threat came from.
</P>
<P>
"We're aware of the closure of U.S. missions in a number of
African countries, and we do maintain close contacts with the
Americans on security matters," the official said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said no diplomatic staff was being evacuated from
the four countries.
</P>
<P>
Bin laden was accused by the United States of plotting the bomb
attacks on U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania last August, which
killed more than 250 people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
