<HEADLINE> U.S. Does not Support Montenegro's Separation from Serbia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Friday that it does not back Montenegro's independence from
Yugoslavia because further disintegration of the federation is not
conducive to the stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
Independence for the republic, junior partner to Serbia in
Yugoslavia, was not necessarily in the interests of Montenegro or
the region, State Department spokesman James Rubin said at a
regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
"The further disintegration of Yugoslavia would not serve to
promote peace and stability in the Balkans," Rubin added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that independence would not be "a panacea for the
challenges that Montenegro faces."
</P>
<P>
Rubin said that working inside Yugoslavia, Montenegro could act
as a force to promote change.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has been demonizing Yugoslav leader
Slobodan Milosevic and believe he is the root cause of the
instability on the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
"Montenegro's active support is important for implementing the
Kosovo settlement and bringing democracy to all the people of
Yugoslavia," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States plans to provide economic aid to Montenegro
in isolation from Serbia.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to do our best to ensure that Montenegro doesn't
suffer as a result of the unwillingness of the West to provide
reconstruction assistance to Belgrade," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
"We're trying to ensure that Kosovo and Montenegro are treated
differently than Serbia and the rest of that territory on the
map," he noted.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to the Balkans, U.S. President Bill Clinton
last week met Montenegrin President Milo Djukanovic and encouraged
him to keep distance from Belgrade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
