<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Urges Containing Israel-lebanon Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 25 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan voiced concern on Friday at the escalation of violence along
the Israel-Lebanon border.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. spokesman said he "calls on the parties to cooperate
with the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL) in containing the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
"Above all, innocent civilians must not be targeted and the
international status of United Nations personnel must be
respected," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Annan is now on a visit to Britain.
</P>
<P>
"Over the last three weeks, UNIFIL had reported an apparent
slackening of control on both sides over their personnel in south
Lebanon, this has affected the civilian population as well as
UNIFIL," spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He said the direct attacks on civilian targets in several areas
of Lebanon and the rocket fire into northern Israel "represent a
serious escalation".
</P>
<P>
"That innocent civilians lost their lives is particularly
deplorable," he added.
</P>
<P>
News reports said Israeli tanks were rolling along the border
with Lebanon following an outbreak of violence Thursday, leaving
eight Lebanese and Israelis dead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
