<DOCNO> XIE19990626.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Existing-Home Sales Fall 4 Percent in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The National Association of
Realtors said Friday that sales of existing homes fell 4 percent
in May as mortgage was on the rise.
</P>
<P>
Sales of existing single-family homes dropped in May to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 5.04 million units, the
Association said. This is the second consecutive monthly decline
after the sales hit an all-time high in March.
</P>
<P>
Under the revised figures, April sales declined 3.1 percent to
a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 5.25 million units. The
Association originally estimated a 3.3 percent drop in April to
5.24 million units.
</P>
<P>
In March, existing-home sales posted a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 5.42 million units, a record high.
</P>
<P>
May's home-sales figure, the lowest level in six months, was
below the expectations of analysts, who predicted that sales would
either hold steady or decline slightly.
</P>
<P>
According to Freddie Mac, the mortgage company, the average
interest rate on a 30-year, fixed-rate mortgage was 7.15 percent
in May, up from 6.92 percent in April. The rate was 7.14 percent
in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
Last month all regions experienced a dip in resales, which is
consistent with the recent increase in mortgage rates.
</P>
<P>
The national median existing-homes sales price rose 3.3 percent
to 133,000 dollars in May compared to May 1998. But the median
existing-homes sale price in May was only 1.8 percent higher than
the median price reported in April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
