<HEADLINE> British Economy Remains Flat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON June 25 (Xinhua) - The UK's economic output remained
broadly flat during the first three months of the year, according
to official figures released Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Office for National Statistics said while revised data
continued to show zero growth in the first quarter compared to the
last three months, year-on-year growth had been revised to 0.7
percent from a previous 0.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
It was the weakest performance for the economy since 1992.
However the figures did show the service sector performing more
strongly than had been thought.
</P>
<P>
Royal Bank of Scotland economist Neil Parker said the revised
GDP data meant "the economy is well set for strong growth in the
second quarter and for the second half of 1999".
</P>
<P>
But signs of economic recovery are still mixed, with some
measures - notably consumer and business confidence, and house
prices - showing strong increases, while others, such as retail
sales, still weak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
