<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Congress' Cooperation on Domestic Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Friday called for Congress' cooperation on domestic issues such as
Medicare, Social Security, education, child care and gun control.
</P>
<P>
"Congress should pass it and I will sign it," Clinton said in a
speech at Georgetown University as he ticked down the same list of
initiatives he outlined five months ago in his State of the Union
address.
</P>
<P>
Republicans in Congress, who are reluctant to cooperate with
Clinton on these issues, showcased their own agenda calling for
measures to bolster the national security, improve education,
safeguard the Social Security surplus for improving the program
and cut taxes.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is trying to reassert his voice in America's political
debate after the 11-week Kosovo conflict with the approach of the
2000 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
"I came back to Washington after my trip to Europe with a
renewed energy for the domestic agenda," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton called for a spirit of bipartisanship and a "season of
progress" on Republican issues while criticizing Republican
leaders for blocking some of his policy proposals.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that ultimately he and the lawmakers would be
judged by "whether we choose to seize this opportunity" or allow
it to be "squandered with petty arguments and animosities in
special interest politics."
</P>
<P>
"I regret to say that the atmosphere in Washington has become
increasingly poisoned by bitter partisanship," he said. "I don't
understand exactly why, since we keep doing better and better
and better in America."  
</P>
