<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK, Ireland Report Progress in N.Irish Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Headway was reportedly made in
easing a deadlock in the Northern Irish peace process during four
hours of talks with the province's main parties in Belfast on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Ministers Tony Blair his Irish counterpart Bertie
Ahern said all the parties to the stalled Good Friday agreement
had backed fundamental principles including guerrilla disarmament
by May 2000 and the creation of a power-sharing provincial
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Despite clear gaps between the parties on core issues, sources
close to the talks said the scene was set for a fresh push to end
the impasse in resumed talks next week.
</P>
<P>
Blair and Ahern arrived in Belfast earlier today in a bid to
bridge a gap between pro-British unionists and Sinn Fein
republicans so as to enable the full implementation of the accord
by a deadline of next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Blair described talks with the parties as "constructive and
good natured," saying they would resume next Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein, the political arm of IRA guerrillas, said it had had
"a good meeting" with the prime ministers and denied that it had
changed tack on the need for disarmament.
</P>
<P>
But David Trimble, the province's First Minister and leader of
the powerful Ulster Unionist Party (UUP) protested that he had not
yet heard Sinn Fein commit itself to the "decommissioning"
(disarmament) of weapons held by its Irish Republican Army (IRA)
ally.
</P>
<P>
"There can be question of bringing a private army into the
heart of the administration unless it has shown it is going to
turn its back irrevocably on violence, and has demonstrated that
by actions," a Reuters report quoted Trimble as telling reporters.
</P>
<P>
In order to kickstart the stalled process, Blair had put forward
a plan that could pave the way for Sinn Fein to enter a ruling
provincial cabinet if the IRA gave and stuck by firm pledges that
it would fully disarm by May 2000.
</P>
<P>
Blair said that while there were still differences between the
parties "about timing and implementation", they were committed to
vital principles.
</P>
<P>
The parties were committed to "an inclusive executive
exercising devolved powers; decommissioning of all paramilitary
arms by May 2000; decommissioning to be carried out in the manner
determined by the Independent Commission on Decommissioning,"
Blair said, calling it "welcome progress."
</P>
<P>
A row about IRA disarmament has stalled the formation of the
executive, which was the pivotal element of last year's peace
deal. as Unionists refuse to sit with Sinn Fein until the IRA
scraps the weaponry that sustained a 30 year onslaught against
rule from Britain. Both sides accuse each other of reneging on the
pact. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
