<HEADLINE> Tanzania Urged to Fight Offshore Drug Trafficking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian Maritime
Foundation, a non-governmental organization, Friday called on the
government to establish a coast guard unit to curb drug
trafficking on the coastline and offshore islands.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the foundation, Sivili Mushi, told the press in Dar
es Salaam that the sea is a major channel of drug transportation,
adding that loopholes for the booming of the drug dealing should
be stemmed.
</P>
<P>
While the government is taking measures against drug
trafficking on land, most of the drugs are transported through
ship containers, said Mushi.
</P>
<P>
He said as a maritime professional organization, his foundation
is resolved to join the Tanzanian government in fighting the
illegal drug trafficking in the east African country.
</P>
<P>
Mushi pointed out that it is necessary for the government to
establish a coast guard unit which will take up the responsibility
of monitoring the sea ferries suspected to be involved in the
transit of drugs.
</P>
<P>
The chairman said some small vessels and islands are used as
distribution points or transshipment centers of drugs.
</P>
<P>
"A coastline unit will not only spot and report illegal drug
traffickers but also assist in combating illegal sailing in
territorial waters, oil pollution and illegal dumping of wastes,
entry of illegal goods and tax evaders," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the maritime foundation congratulated the government
for the initiative of observing the World Anti-drug Day which
falls on June 26. It added that the move reflects seriousness in
fighting the drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The theme of this year's World Anti-drug Day is "Music Against
Drugs" and Tanzanian Prime Minister Frederick Sumaye is expected
to launch the United Nations International Drug Control Program
(UNDCP) country program in the Tanzanian capital Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
