<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Urged to Encourage Breast-feeding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The African governments must
continue encouraging breast-feeding irrespective of HIV infection
rates, a World Health Organization (WHO) official said in Harare
Friday.
</P>
<P>
WHO secretariat head Liz Mason told delegates attending the
three-day regional Integrated Management of Childhood Illness
(IMCI) meeting that the actual transmission of the HIV virus from
mother to child through breast- feeding depends on the prevalence
rate in pregnant women.
</P>
<P>
The WHO official said that chances of transmission of the virus
through breast-feeding are very slim and stand at only 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
"As a general principle and irrespective of HIV infection
rates, breast- feeding should continue to be promoted, protected
and supported," she said.
</P>
<P>
Breast-feeding is important because it stimulates the
development of an infant's own immune system, giving it an active
protection against infections, she added.
</P>
<P>
Mason noted that most of the substances found in breast milk
are not present in its substitutes which could contribute to
premature deaths of children.
</P>
<P>
She said health workers should come up with effective
strategies to assist infected mothers to make decisions that do
not compromise the health of their children.
</P>
<P>
HIV positive mothers have been faced with a dilemma of whether
or not to breast-feed their babies for fear of infecting them with
the virus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
