<HEADLINE> Many African Children Die Due To Medicine Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Delegates to the three-day regional
 Integrated Management of Childhood Illness (IMCI) workshop in
Harare expressed their concern Friday that many children die in
Africa as a result of medicine shortage.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization (WHO) estimated that about 12
million children die every year in Africa from diseases such as
acute respiratory infections, diarrhoea, measles and malaria, the
Zimbabwean News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"The experiences in Tanzania, Madagascar and other countries
have shown that essential drugs are always in short supply,
compromising the health of the people especially infants," the
delegates said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe had recently been experiencing a shortage of essential
 medicines as well.
</P>
<P>
The delegates said the issue of medicine shortage was supposed
to be resolved seriously when countries implemented reforms in the
health sector.
</P>
<P>
They said other setbacks in tackling childhood illness included
lack of funding by governments and lack of proper training of
medical staff.
</P>
<P>
The workshop was aimed at improving the implementation of the
childhood illness program through information sharing among
countries.
</P>
<P>
The program was started in Africa some four years ago with an
aim of improving management of childhood illness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
