<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President Blames Old Guard for Ruining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
Friday blamed the old guard for ruining the ruling Zimbabwe
African National Union by putting their personal ambitions first.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe, who is also president of the ruling party, said it is
disturbing that personal disagreements among the old guard
continue to affect the party in a number of provinces.
</P>
<P>
"If that persists we shall soon be compelled to dub them
witches of the party, in which case it may be necessary to
undertake an exercise of exorcism," Mugabe said when opening the
38th ordinary session of the ruling party's central committee.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe News Agency quoted the president as saying there
is an urgent need to correct the internal contradictions so that
the party could be able to face the electorate in the year 2000
general elections.
</P>
<P>
He said it is disturbing to note that while contradictions have
been solved in some areas others remain permanently divided.
</P>
<P>
The party is facing factions in most of its provinces which are
 threatening its collapse, the agency reported.
</P>
<P>
On the drafting of the new constitution, Mugabe said that the
party's central committee will meet soon to debate its position on
the constitution.
</P>
<P>
It is unfortunate that the party's legal committee has not yet
provided its ideas for discussion, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean government recently appointed a Constitutional
Review Commission with the view of drafting a new constitution to
replace the British-authored 1979 Lancaster House constitution
which is said not to represent the interests of Zimbabweans.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said after the drafting stage, the government would
undertake a referendum for its approval in which registered voters
would vote for or against it. 
</P>
