<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Kills Nine in Southeastern Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Nine people have been killed by
flood in southeastern Bangladesh's Chittagong and Cox's Bazar
districts where the flood situation has worsened, reports reaching
here said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Heavy downpour has brought fresh areas under water, and the
situation has been aggravated by water sliding down the hills in
the two districts.
</P>
<P>
A preliminary report said at least 4,000 houses were demolished
in the districts by the flood water rendering tens of thousands of
people homeless, and a huge number of cattle heads and poultry
birds perished, with 870 kilometers of unpaved and 105 paved roads
damaged.
</P>
<P>
In Bandarban, one of the country's three southeastern hill
districts, some 20,000 homes have been inundated by water.
</P>
<P>
The BSS news agency reported Saturday that two rivers in the
southeastern region were flowing above their respective danger
levels during the past 24 hours, and the Brahmaputra-Jamuna and
the Padma rivers marked further rise at all points.
</P>
<P>
But all the rivers in the Ganges and Meghna basins were flowing
below the danger level, the BSS said.
</P>
<P>
Monsoon is now active over Bangladesh, with moderate to very
heavy rainfall recorded at all places in the country during the
last 24 hours, according to the Flood Information Center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990626.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The following is economic briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Saudi Arabian government adopted a series of
measures to control cigarette smuggling from neighboring Yemen as
the smuggled stuff sell in the kingdom at prices 35 percent lower
than local ones.
</P>
<P>
Saudi trade ministry sources said the smuggled cigarettes
consume 90 percent of the southern kingdom markets, up to Jeddah
on the eastern coast of the Red sea, the Cairo-based Al Alam Al
Yom newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted the sources as saying that the 50 cigarette
box gross sells at 1,250 Saudi Riyals (333 U.S. dollars) while the
tax-added prices hit 1,890 Riyals (504 dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Saudi authorities impose 100 percent taxes on tobacco
products in a bid to control tobacco consumption for protecting
the public health.
</P>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- The current farming season in Sudan is facing
difficulties and challenges as a result of low finance and failure
by farmers to repay their due debts estimated at billions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sources with the Ministry of Agriculture was quoted Saturday by
the Al Alam Al Yom newspaper as saying that the concerned
organizations are striving to market 600,000 tons of corn and
to find ways to provide cash for the current summer season.
</P>
<P>
As a result, preparations for the new season have been slowed
down despite a good rainy season. Although 38,940 acres (16,354.8
hectares) were planned for growing corn in Gezira, the largest
farming land in the country, only 26 percent of the land is ready
for farming.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- The worst drought experienced by Iran in 30 years
this season has damaged 3.3 billion U.S. dollars worth of crops,
said Iranian Minister of Agriculture Issa Kalantari.
</P>
<P>
The low rain precipitation hit hard fruit, crop and farming
production with an estimated loss of 10 billion Riyals (3.3
billion dollars), Saturday's London-based Al Hayat Arabic language
newspaper quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
Rainfalls shrank by 40 percent compared with those of last
year, with the northwestern areas hit the most by the drought.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has authorized digging up 6,500 wells to make up
for the lack of rain water.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The construction of an oil pipeline agreed upon by
Jordan and Iraq last year will be delayed for sometime as a result
of economic problems, said a Jordanian official.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Energy and Mineral Resources Suleiman Abu Ileim was
quoted by Saturday's London-based Arabic language newspaper Al
Shark Al Awsat as saying that the economic hardships faced by
Jordan at present are well known.
</P>
<P>
At this stage, the Jordanian government will maintain an
agreement stipulating for spending 40 million dinnars (75 million
U.S. dollars) annually to cover 72 percent of the total cost of
shipping Iraqi oil to Jordan, with Iraq financing the rest of the
28 percent of costs.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Iraq agreed last year to construct a 750-
kilometer-long pipeline at a cost of 350 million dollars between a
pumping station located at 260 kilometers northwest of Baghdad and
the Zarga oil refinery northeast of Amman.
</P>
<P>
The minister affirmed his country's hopes to contribute to
developing the Iraqi oil fields.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1991 Gulf war, Iraq has been providing Jordan with
75,000 barrels of oil per day, almost covering Jordan's total
needs of oil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
