<DOCNO> XIE19990626.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UIA's 20th World Congress Closes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The 20th World Congress of the
International Union of Architects (UIA) closed here tonight in the
China Ethnic Culture Park.
</P>
<P>
During the four-day congress, more than 6,000 of the world's
top architects from over 100 countries and regions delivered
academic reports and exchanged ideas on topics such as the
relationship between architecture and the environment, and between
architecture and culture.
</P>
<P>
The congress also sponsored a series of exhibitions featuring
the achievements of Chinese architects and their counterparts all
over the globe, and held an international student architecture
design competition.
</P>
<P>
One important moment came this morning, when the congress
passed the Beijing Charter, a formal document of the congress
drafted by Wu Liangyong, vice-president of the Architectural
Society of China and a professor at Qinghua University.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the congress said that the document will serve
as a "road map" for world architectural development in the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
In her closing speech, UIA President Sara Topelson de Grinberg
thanked the Chinese government for its full support for the
congress.
</P>
<P>
She said that the congress explored and analyzed the trends of
world architectural development, and made it possible for
architects worldwide to conduct wide-ranging exchanges and promote
common understanding, which will exert a great influence on
architectural development in the next century.
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony, Yu Zhengsheng, president of the congress'
organizing committee and minister of construction, presented
awards to Wu Liangyong and Zhan Qinnan, vice-president of the
Architectural Society of China, for their painstaking efforts in
the preparations for the congress.
</P>
<P>
The UIA world congress of UIA is held every three years; the
next congress will be held in Berlin, capital of Germany, in 2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
