<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistani Prime Minister to Visit China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif will be paying a working visit to China from June 28 to
July 3 at the invitation of his Chinese counterpart, announced the
Pakistani Foreign Office Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Sharif is scheduled to hold an in-depth exchange of views with
the Chinese leadership on a wide range of subjects including
political, economic, regional and international issues, according
to a Foreign Office press release.
</P>
<P>
Special focus will be placed on security, peace and economic
development in the region against the backdrop of the current
volatile situation in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
In Beijing, Sharif will hold talks with Chinese Premier Zhu
Rongji, call on Chinese President Jiang Zemin and meet with Li
Peng, chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the two sides are expected to sign several
agreements. They will also exchange the instruments regarding
Pakistan's establishment of consular relations with Macao which
will return to China in December this year.
</P>
<P>
After his three-day stay in Beijing, Sharif will proceed to
Kunming where an international horticulture exhibition is being
held.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister will also visit Hong Kong where he will meet
with Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa.
</P>
<P>
Sharif visited China in 1991, 1992 and 1998 as the prime
minister of Pakistan and in 1996 as the opposition leader.
</P>
</TEXT>
