<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Delegation Heads for Damascus for Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 26 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi national assembly
delegation left here on Saturday, heading for Damascus, Syria to
participate in the 34th session of the Arab Parliamentary
Federation's Council (APFC) due to be held on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Ghanim Khadori, head of the delegation, said in a statement
that Iraq will put forward a proposal aimed at achieving Arab
solidarity and confronting the challenges besetting the Arab
nation's security, according to the Iraqi News Agency before
departure.
</P>
<P>
Khadori, who is the deputy speaker of the Iraqi parliament,
said the Iraqi delegation will take part in the discussions on
the declaration of the formation of Arab Common Market
Parliamentary Committee.
</P>
<P>
The deputy speaker also said the Iraqi delegation will hold
talks with Arab parliamentarians on the implementation of the
decisions adopted at the session of the Arab Parliamentary Union
(APU) held in Amman, Jordan last year.
</P>
<P>
At the APU's Amman session held last December after the
U.S and Britain launched airstrikes against Iraq, the APU called
on Arab governments to condemn the airstrikes and work for the
lifting of the U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990626.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Parliament Passes Budget Bill In First Reading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's House of
Representatives Saturday passed the government-proposed budget
bill for fiscal year 2000 in the first reading.
</P>
<P>
Some 247 legislators voted in favor of the 860 billion baht
(23.2 billion U.S. dollars) budget bill, while 90 voted against
it.
</P>
<P>
The budget, a 4.2 percent increase from the previous one,
carries a 110-billion-baht (2.97 billion U.S. dollars) deficit, or
2.2 percent of GDP, based on the government's capability to
generate a revenue of only 750 billion baht (20.2 billion U.S.
dollars) from tax collection.
</P>
<P>
This is believed to show the government's resolution to
stimulate the economy by increasing government expenditure at a
time when private consumption is weak.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day debate on the budget bill, the opposition
argued that the government's optimism over the economic recovery
was misplaced, quoting sluggish exports, falling interest rates
and stunted public spending power as the reasons.
</P>
<P>
They also said the investment funding is too meager to spur the
recovery.
</P>
<P>
However, the coalition government, led by Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai, said significant government spending on large-scale
job-creation, education promotion and public welfare projects will
accelerate the economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
The six-party coalition holds a 254-seat majority in the
383-strong lower house. Ten seats of the originally 393-member
parliament have been vacant due to deaths and resignations.
</P>
<P>
The budget bill will undergo second and third readings in the
lower house before being presented to the Senate for further
discussions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
