<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Peacekeepers to Enter Kosovo in Batches in 40-45 Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Russian peacekeepers will enter
Kosovo group by group in 40-45 days, and will stay there till June
10, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Leonid Ivashov, head of the Defense Ministry's International
Cooperation Department, said here Saturday that Russia sent its
first military transport aircraft to Kosovo earlier Saturday,
carrying airport service personnel and navigation equipment to the
Slatina Airport.
</P>
<P>
About 200 Russian troops are stationed in the Slatina airport
near Pristina, capital of Kosovo. Moscow said the airport will be
under the control of its peacekeepers, with access available to
NATO peacekeeping forces.
</P>
<P>
The second aircraft with Russian peacekeeping troops "is ready
to take off on Monday," Ivashov said. "The advance group of guards
will ensure the safe arrival of the main peacekeeping contingent."
</P>
<P>
The Russian peacekeepers will also go by sea and by railway.
Part of the contingent might be shipped via the Greek port of
Salonica.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that Greece will help with a safe move of our
peacekeepers within its territory," the Interfax news agency
quoted Ivashov as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We do not see the need for the Russian Navy in the Adriatic
Sea. We are there for peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
Early on Saturday, President Boris Yeltsin signed a decree on
sending Russia's military contingent to participate in the Kosovo
international peacekeeping operation.
</P>
<P>
According to the decree, about 3,600 troops will be deployed in
Kosovo and their assignment will be completed till June 10, 2000.
</P>
<P>
The General Headquarters of the Russian Armed Forces will be in
command of the contingent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 210 Russian interior troops with the international
police presence and 30 Federal Border Guard Service personnel will
be subordinated to a special envoy of the U.N. secretary-general.
</P>
</TEXT>
