<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Now Gets Funds From All Directions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- China's central government used to
be the only investor in Tibet for decades, but in recent years,
this southwest China ethnic autonomous region has successfully
widened its channels of investment.
</P>
<P>
Between 1959, the year the democratic reform was launched after
a failed rebellion by the Dalai Lama, and 1998, the central
government pumped more than 40 billion yuan into Tibet. This was
mainly used for a large number of capital projects.
</P>
<P>
Since then, inland provinces and cities have been asked by the
central leadership to offer helping hands for Tibet in various
ways. So far, 105 key projects and 1,000 smaller ones have been
jointly funded by the central government and inland areas,
involving a total investment of 2.9 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Tibet has been encouraged to use other financial
channels such as getting loans from commercial banks, obtaining
foreign assistance, and floating the stocks of local state-owned
companies on the country's fledgling stock market.
</P>
<P>
In 1989 alone, Tibetan companies, farmers and herdsmen were
granted 7.8 billion yuan in loans by local commercial banking
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, Tibet has received 51 million U.S.
dollars in assistance from foreign companies and individuals, and
66 million U.S. dollars in the form of soft loans from foreign
governments.
</P>
<P>
Currently, overseas investors are engaged in nine development
projects in Tibet, with a contractual capital of 24 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the investment pluralism policy, government funding
now stands at less than 40 percent of Tibet's total, compared with
68 percent five years ago, according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
The Tibetan economy has been growing at a rate of 12 percent
annually, faster than the national average of about nine percent,
for five years in succession. The increase in investment has
contributed to 75 percent of its rapid economic growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990626.0070 </DOCNO>
