<DOCNO> XIE19990626.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chiluba: Preparation for DRC Peace Goes "Extremely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick Chiluba
said here Saturday that the official meeting to make preparations
for the regional summit on peace in the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC) is going on here "extremely well."
</P>
<P>
Chiluba, who was mandated by Southern African Development
Community (SADC) to mediate a peace solution to the 11-month war
in the DRC, told a press conference that a good result is coming
out and consultations will continue and are expected to end some
time Saturday.
</P>
<P>
After that, ministers will take over to pave the way for the
summit, at which a ceasefire agreement is expected to be signed
for an end to the conflict in the third largest African country,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said presidents of the countries concerned are kept
informed about the preparations.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Salim Ahmed Salim, secretary-general of
the Organization of African Unity (OAU), said the OAU is active
from the very beginning of the conflict in support of the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
He said the consultations here are in the right direction
toward peace.
</P>
<P>
All the belligerents have been involved for the first time in
the preparatory meeting and the meeting is going on with a
constructive spirit of give and take and desire to find a lasting
peace.
</P>
<P>
Salim praised Zambia for its peace effort in DRC.
</P>
<P>
To show OAU's support for the peace effort, Salim donated
50,000 U.S. dollars to Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
He also said the officials have done a good job for the summit,
which was scheduled for Saturday and has been postponed because
final documents have not been ready.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Vice President Christon Tembo said here Friday that the
summit may take place here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He said the summit will be delayed because consultation talks
are still going on and the preparation of the final documents for
the summit won't be ready until Saturday. In addition, some
issues still need to be sort out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
