<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Marks International Drug Control Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Passers-by in downtown Beijing
were told "Treasure your life by keeping away from narcotics" by
anti-drug campaigners, while Guangdong Province publicly destroyed
drugs today, as parts of activities held across China to mark the
worldwide movement against drug crimes.
</P>
<P>
Apart from publicity activities on major streets, 360
volunteers in Beijing pledged to devote themselves to educational
work for drug prevention and control.
</P>
<P>
As the Internal Day Against Drug Abuse and Illicit Trafficking
fell today, Beijing led other Chinese cities in holding massive
campaigns to ring the alarm bells against rampant drug use and
trafficking among the general public.
</P>
<P>
"The situation (of drug abuse and trafficking in China) remains
very serious, since drug-related crimes are growing increasingly
rampant both at home and abroad," acknowledged Jia Chunwang,
director of the National Narcotics Control Commission.
</P>
<P>
Jia, who is also the Minister of Public Security, joined anti-
drug campaigners in front of a Beijing shopping center to hand out
publicity materials to passers-by.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in Humen in south China's Guangdong Province, 200 kg
of heroin and 200 kg of the drug "ice" were burned today in front
of some 3,000 locals from all walks of life.
</P>
<P>
A total of 320,000 primary and middle school students in
Dongguan participated in a rally to respond a call by Guangdong's
Party Secretary Li Changchun for compulsory education in drug
prevention among local people older than ten years.
</P>
<P>
So far, student narcotics control committees have been set up
in 686 colleges and schools in Dongguan, having some 320,000
student members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990626.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Iraqi Legislator Briefs Annan on Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Speaker of the Iraqi Parliament
Saadoun Hammadi told U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan that over
1.11 million Iraqis have died of shortage of medicines and more
than 10 million others are suffering from malnutrition as a result
of U.N. santions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In a letter intended to brief Annan on the consequences brought
about by the sanctions since 1990, Hammadi also said the embargo
has affected the environment as well as the educational, cultural
and all social aspects in Iraq, the Iraqi News Agency reported on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The pollution rate for the drinking water has reached 50
percent, the speaker added.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Hammadi slammed the U.N. Sanctions Committee
for blocking the approval of Iraqi contracts signed with foreign
companies under the oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
He said the oil-for-food program, which allows Iraq to export
limited amount of oil to buy food, medicine and other
humanitarian supplies for its people, have sustained premeditated
troubles incurred by the U.S. and British governments.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has long accused the U.S. and British representatives in
the Sanctions Committee of putting on hold its contracts to
purchase oil spare parts and medical appliances under flimsy
pretexts.
</P>
<P>
Hammadi also said the Iraqi economy has been greatly damaged by
the continued embargo, adding Iraq has suffered a total loss of
120 billion U.S. dollars since the imposition of U.N. sanctions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
