<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Should Do More to Tackle Air Pollution: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- China's capital should do a lot
more to get rid of its serious air pollution, China's top
environment-protection official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The situation has raised concern throughout society, according
to Xie Zhenghua, director of the State Environmental Protection
Administration (SEPA).
</P>
<P>
Official monitors indicate that the levels of suspended
particles, sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide in the city's air
were on average 89, 100 and 204 percent higher, respectively, than
the good air quality level.
</P>
<P>
And in 1998, Beijing's overall air pollution index ranked the
third highest of all cities in the world, higher even than that of
Mexico city.
</P>
<P>
"As China's political and cultural center, Beijing's
environment shouldn't be like this," Xie told the 10th meeting of
the Standing Committee of the Ninth National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
Since last winter, the municipal authorities have taken a
series of measures to tackle air pollution, which has produced
some initial results.
</P>
<P>
"However, the city must make unremitting efforts to solve the
problem, and reverse the trend of environmental degradation," he
said.
</P>
<P>
It is learned that the city and the SEPA are adding the
finishing touches to an environmental protection blueprint, which
is to be submitted to the State Council for approval in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, Beijing will make some improvements in
its environment before this October, obvious improvements by the
end of 2000 and national-level improvements by the end of 2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
