<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Bank Announces Restructuring Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Development Bank of
Singapore Ltd. (DBS Bank), the largest local bank in Singapore,
Saturday announced a proposed scheme to restructure DBS Bank as a
wholly-owned subsidiary of a financial services holding company
proposed to be known as DBS Group Holdings Ltd. (DBSH).
</P>
<P>
The proposed restructuring will involve the incorporation of
DBSH in Singapore, the cancellation of all the issued DBS Bank
shares in exchange for new DBSH shares on one-for-one basis, the
issue of new DBS Bank shares to DBSH, and the delisting of DBS
Bank as well as the listing of DBSH on the Main Board of the Stock
Exchange of Singapore (SES).
</P>
<P>
DBS Bank expressed its belief that the proposed restructuring
will provide greater strategic, financial and managerial
flexibility in organizing its operations and implementing its
strategy to expand regionally and across product lines in
financial services.
</P>
<P>
DBS Bank expects the restructuring to provide additional
flexibility and ease in structuring acquisitions and new
businesses, to facilitate increased management focus on strategic
goals to maximize shareholder returns and to position the DBS Bank
group to take advantage of potential capital, tax and other
operating efficiencies.
</P>
<P>
In its announcement, DBS Bank also made a proposal to release
the government from its restriction on selling non-voting shares
in the capital of DBS Bank.
</P>
<P>
DBS Bank acquired the respective business undertakings of the
government-owned Post Office Savings Bank (POSB) in September 1998
and in the agreement relating to the POSB transaction between the
government and the DBS Bank, the government undertook that, prior
to January 1, 2002, it would not sell to any person other than a
wholly-owned entity any non-voting shares issued to it or any
ordinary shares converted from the non-voting shares.
</P>
<P>
The proposed restructuring is subject to the approval of the
relevant authorities, including the Monetary Authority of
Singapore. The SES has granted in-principle approval for the
restructuring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
