<DOCNO> XIE19990626.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rule of Law Preserved in HK: Chief Executive (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Chief Executive Tung
Chee Hwa said here Saturday that he has confidence in the
preservation of the integrity of Hong Kong's legal system and the
rule of law under the "one country, two systems" policy.
</P>
<P>
Tung made the remarks at a press conference on the
interpretation of the Basic Law provisions concerning the right of
abode (ROA) issue by the Standing Committee of China's National
People's Congress (NPC).
</P>
<P>
The NPC Standing Committee issued its interpretation earlier
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"We have seen once again that the central authorities are most
concerned about Hong Kong's prosperity and stability. I can say
that with great confidence that under "one country, two Systems",
the integrity of Hong Kong's legal system and the rule of law will
be preserved," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
Over a month ago, Tung said, the Special Administrative Region
(SAR) government "decided to seek the assistance of the State
Council to approach the NPC Standing Committee to interpret the
Basic Law provisions concerning the right of abode according to
their true legislative intent, and to help us resolve the
difficulties we had encountered in implementing the Basic Law."
</P>
<P>
"A problem, which concerns the long-term interests of Hong Kong
people and which has caused widespread public concern, has finally
been resolved in a manner which is entirely legal and
constitutional," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
The chief executive emphasized that the SAR government
"treasures the rule of law as one of the most important pillars of
Hong Kong's success."
</P>
<P>
"In dealing with the right of abode issue, we have exercised
great care to ensure that every step taken is strictly in line
with the law and complies with applicable procedures," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that it is "understandable" that some Hong Kong
people who do not fully appreciate the situation may be worried
that the rule of law has been affected by this issue.
</P>
<P>
"I wish to assure these people ... we will never permit the
rule of law be compromised. In fact mainstream community opinion
supports the interpretation by the NPC Standing Committee. They
have made a realistic assessment of Hong Kong's overall interests,
such as employment opportunities and quality of life, and support
our effort to resolve this matter within the established legal
framework," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Basically, the problem has now been resolved in accordance
with this approach," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that it is "perfectly understandable" that some
problems may arise during the implementation of the "historically
unprecedented "one country, two systems" policy.
</P>
<P>
"So long as we keep Hong Kong's best interests at heart, and so
long as we act in strict compliance with the spirit of the rule of
law and the Basic Law itself, we will be able to cope with any
difficulties," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Through this effort, we have enriched our experience in
implementing and enforcing the Basic Law, as well as in
safeguarding the rule of law in Hong Kong," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990626.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nine Scientific Innovation Centers Built in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Academy of Sciences (
CAS) has built nine scientific innovation centers in the fields of
basic scientific studies, hi-tech development and environmental
research.
</P>
<P>
The centers are aimed at meeting the needs of the state's
strategic development program and promoting the development of key
industries, according to the academy.
</P>
<P>
The four centers for basic scientific research are the Beijing
Mathematics Research Center, the Beijing Materials Science
Research Center, the Shanghai Life Science Research Center and the
State Astronomical Research Center.
</P>
<P>
The three centers for hi-tech development, which were built on
the basis of cooperation between research institutes and
enterprises, are the Shanghai High-Technology Development Center,
the Northeast High-Performance Materials and Advanced
Manufacturing Technology Research and Development Center and the
Beijing Information Science and Technology Research Center.
</P>
<P>
To better use and protect natural resources and solve
environmental problems, CAS has built the Beijing Geo-Sciences
Research Center and the Northwest Resources, Environment and
Sustainable Development Research Center.
</P>
<P>
It also plans to build a research center in southwest China to
study the proper use of biological resources and the protection of
bio-diversity.
</P>
<P>
CAS has put the issue of protecting and improving the living
environment of mankind on the top of its agenda since it was
founded 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
To date, it has cooperated with more than 40 research
institutes in this area, and established more than 80 biological
stations across the country to do environmental and biological
research.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the construction of innovation centers, the CAS
has also selected a group of institutes to practice the modern
research institute system, and experiment with reform of the
structure and management of scientific institutes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990626.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Pak-China Ties Conducive to Regional Peace, Security: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said Saturday the friendly relations between his country
and China help reinforce stability and security in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
"I am fully satisfied with our bilateral relations because,
apart of being of mutual benefit, they help to strengthen
stability and security in the region, for China is a great bulwark
of peace," Sharif said while talking to a group of Islamabad-base
Chinese correspondents at the Prime Minister's House.
</P>
<P>
However, the prime minister, who will leave next Monday for a
seven-day visit to China, expressed his belief that the bilateral
ties between the two neighbors should be further promoted,
particularly in the economic field.
</P>
<P>
"We have much to learn from China in the sphere of advanced
technology," he said. "That is why there is need to add more
substance to our relationship."
</P>
<P>
While speaking highly of the achievements made by China, Sharif
said, Pakistan has been looking "with admiration" at the
"spectacular progress" made by China in the last 50 years,
particularly during the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister labeled the reunion of Hong Kong with its
motherland and economic strides of China as "nothing short of a
miracle," which "heralds a new and powerful role for China in the
councils of the world."
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that "China will emerge as a great
power in the coming century."
</P>
<P>
"This should impart a feeling of security and confidence to the
developing world which has always looked up to China as a champion
of its political and economic interests," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sharif has visited China several times in his capacity both as
prime minister and as opposition leader. Sharif's forthcoming
visit to China is the second since he resumed his premiership in
February 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
