<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 12:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Mubarak's U.S. Trip Aimed at </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Peace in the Mideast and trade will
be on top of the agenda during Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's
six-day visit to the United States starting Saturday, which is
aimed at boosting bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
That Egypt is a key Arab ally of the United States in the
Middle East did not stop Cairo and Washington from differing over
the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to bridge the gap, Mubarak will expound to
U.S. President Bill Clinton and senior U.S. officials Egypt's
position on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The election as prime minister of Ehud Barak, leader of
Israel's Labor Party, last month has raised hopes for reviving the
long-stalled Arab-Israeli peace talks. Both Egypt and the U.S.,
key mediators in the peace process, have welcomed the development.
</P>
<P>
But the two countries are in dispute over Arabs' attitude
toward realizing peace with the Jewish state. Washington wants the
Arabs to show greater flexibility to the peacemaking and economic
cooperation with Israel in a bid to encourage Barak, according to
Egyptian officials.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, meanwhile, adopts a wait-and-see attitude before Barak
carries out his promises to push ahead talks with the Palestinians
and resume negotiations with Syria and Lebanon, which have been
stalled since early 1996.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Mubarak will reiterate Egypt's position that
the Mideast peace process should be based on the land-for-peace
principle and the relevant United Nations resolutions, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak will ask the U.S. to urge Israel to implement the Wye
accord signed last year with the Palestinians, calling for more
Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank. Egypt opposes the
Palestinian-Israeli final-status talks before the implementation
of the Wye accord.
</P>
<P>
Egypt hopes it will yield U.S. understanding and even support
for its stand in an effort to safeguard, to the gratest extent,
Arab's interests in the peace talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Another priority in Mubarak's U.S. trip is to strengthen
economic and trade ties with the U.S., Egypt's second largest
trade partner after the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Local press reported that during Mubarak's visit, Egypt and the
U.S. will sign three agreements on trade, investment and technical
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Trade officials of Egypt hope that negotiations will be held
for the establishment of a free trade zone with the U.S. in a bid
to boost Egyptian exports and finally balance the bilateral trade
with Egypt now on the deficit side. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990626.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Airforce Bombs Eritrean Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian airforce bombed
Eritrea's Assab airport, a strategic military target, at 10:00 am
Saturday morning, the Ethiopian government spokesman said in a
press release.
</P>
<P>
The airport runway was severely damaged as a result of the air
raid, said the release.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the statement claimed that the fighting was
initiated by the Eritrean army in the vicinity of the Mereb River
Friday continued Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Ever since Ethiopia's victorious Operation Sunset in late
February, Eritrea has launched a number of offensives on this
front in an attempt to recapture Badme," the release claimed.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea blamed each other for initiating more
fighting in the wake of renewed calls from the Organization of
Africa Unity (OAU) and the U.N. Security Council for immediate and
unconditional cease-fire between the two Horn of Africa countries.
</P>
<P>
Friday's offensive comes after a one-week lull in hostilities.
Prior to that, there had been intense fighting around the Mereb
River from June 9 to 17.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian defense forces claimed to have put over 24,450
Eritrean soldiers out of action, whereas Asmara said its forces
had killed and wounded more than 18,000 Ethiopian soldiers during
the week-long fighting.
</P>
<P>
The war between the two Horn of Africa neighbors broke out in
early May of 1998 over a disputed stretch of their border.
</P>
<P>
Both countries have agreed to a peace framework put forward by
the OAU, but neither seems to have turned their words into action.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
