<HEADLINE> Ethnic Clash Kills 7 in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Seven were feared dead Friday in
Ibadan, capital of Nigeria's western state Oyo, during a clash
between Hausa-Fulani cattle rearers and traders at a popular
market.
</P>
<P>
A large amount of cows, vehicles and shops were destroyed in
the violence that lasted more than seven hours in the market
called Bodija. The Guardian newspaper reported Saturday,
</P>
<P>
Police said seven persons died, 24 vehicles were burnt while 30
shops were completely razed.
</P>
<P>
Oyo State Governor Alhaji Lam Adesina, in a swift reaction,
visited the market to assess the extent of damage. He ordered an
immediate shift of the cattle market to another location to be
announced soon by the government.
</P>
<P>
The incident started at 8 a.m. Friday following reports that a
young man who was allegedly stabbed by a Hausa man died Thursday
evening.
</P>
<P>
The man, reportedly a load carrier, was said to have been
stabbed in the eye as a result of a misunderstanding over a goat.
The Hausa man was immediately arrested and detained at the Bodija
Police Station.
</P>
<P>
When the traders learnt of the death of the young man, they
went to the police post to inform the police of the development,
but became furious upon the information that the Hausa man had
since been released without further enquiry into the incident.
</P>
<P>
The clash almost degenerated to an ethnic clash between the
ethnic Hausa and the Yoruba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
