<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Adopts Interpretation To Controversial HK Mini-Constitution (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The National People's Congress (
NPC), China's top legislature, adopted here today an
interpretation to two parts of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) Basic Law, which, following a
verdict of the SAR's Court of Final Appeal early this year, have
aroused great controversy in Hong Kong over the past few months.
</P>
<P>
The two parts are Section 4, Article 22 and Item 3 of Section 2,
Article 24 of the HKSAR Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
The first stipulates that "Chinese people in regions other than
Hong Kong must first apply for approval before entering the HKSAR",
while the latter states that permanent Hong Kong residents include
those Chinese nationals who are children of permanent Hong Kong
residents but were born outside Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In a ruling it gave on January 29 this year, the Hong Kong
Court of Final Appeal said that all children born to permanent
Hong Kong residents in the interior areas of China, including
those who were born before their parents became permanent Hong
Kong residents, can naturally obtain right of abode in Hong Kong,
and that these children do not need the approval of relevant
departments in the interior areas to enter and stay in the Hong
Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
A survey showed that this court ruling would grant at least 1.
67 million people in the interior areas the right of abode in Hong
Kong, and that an influx of these people into Hong Kong could
cause serious employment and other social crises in the region.
</P>
<P>
Holding a different view on how to interpret the Basic Law
stipulations, the HKSAR government on May 20 submitted a report to
the State Council in Beijing, asking the Standing Committee of the
NPC to use its authority to explain the controversial parts of the
law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990626.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Set Up System to Deal With Institutional Irregularities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- China is planning to set up a
system to deal with irregularities and crimes committed by
government departments and institutions, according to Auditor
General Li Jinhua here today.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the 10th meeting of the Ninth National People
's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee on the auditing of the
execution of the previous budget, Li said that grave
irregularities and crimes have been uncovered.
</P>
<P>
Some departments and institutions have embezzled large amounts
of fiscal allocations, some have wasted a lot and others have
defrauded the government for their own benefit, said Li, the top
official at the National Audit Office of China.
</P>
<P>
The current system can deal effectively with individuals who
commit economic crimes, but often proves too weak to deal with
crimes committed by government departments and institutions, he
said.
</P>
<P>
To solve the problem, the State Council is considering setting
up a new system to prosecute departments that have embezzled
special funds and caused heavy losses and waste, and punish those
responsible as a result of dereliction of duty and bureaucratic
behavior, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
