<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Adopts Interpretation To Controversial HK Mini-Constitution (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The (HKSAR) Court of Final Appeal did not ask the NPC Standing
Committee to offer an interpretation of the controversial part of
the Basic Law before it gave its verdict, and the court's own
interpretation of the law also failed to comply with our original
legislative spirit," said Qiao Xiaoyang, deputy director of the
Ninth NPC Standing Committee's Legislative Affairs Committee, at
the Standing Committee's ongoing 10th session.
</P>
<P>
According to the NPC interpretation adopted today, the term "
Chinese people in regions other than Hong Kong" used in Section 4,
Article 22 of the HKSAR Basic Law refers to all people living in
various provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities across
China, including Chinese nationals who were born to permanent Hong
Kong residents in the interior areas.
</P>
<P>
"All these people, if they, for whatever reasons, want to enter
the HKSAR, must first apply to the relevant departments in the
places where they live, and wait for approval. And they will not
be allowed to enter the HKSAR unless they hold valid papers issued
by the relevant departments," according to the interpretation.
</P>
<P>
Explaining Item 3 of Section 2, Article 24, the interpretation
says that the precondition for the children of permanent Hong Kong
residents in the interior areas to automatically obtain the right
of abode in Hong Kong is that at least one parent was already a
permanent Hong Kong resident at the time birth.
</P>
<P>
The NPC says that after its release the interpretation should
be applied in relevant cases handled by all courts in the HKSAR.
However, it says, those who have already obtained the right of
abode in the HKSAR as a result of the Hong Kong Court of Final
Appeal's January 29 verdict "will not be affected".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
