<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Kashmir Dispute Central to Pak-India Ties:PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said Saturday that the Jammu and Kashmir dispute is central
to the Pakistani-Indian relations and lasting peace between the
two countries could only come about when the dispute is resolved.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with a group of Islamabad-based Chinese correspondents
at the Prime Minister's House, Sharif said: "Lasting peace between
India and Pakistan can only come about if and when India adopts a
positive attitude and agrees to resolve the Jammu and Kashmir
dispute."
</P>
<P>
"It is imperative that it (India) enters into a dialogue with
Pakistan," Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
Sharif also called on the international community to "play an
active role in trying to unravel this tangled knot which continues
to threaten regional peace and stability."
</P>
<P>
Answering a question about the on-going armed conflict in the
Kashmir area between Pakistan and India, Sharif said that "the
current tensions on the Line of Control are nothing but a facet of
the 52-year-old difference of opinion on the future of Jammu and
Kashmir State."
</P>
<P>
He reiterated Pakistan's position on the long-running Kashmir
dispute that the destiny of the Kashmir people should be decided
by themselves in accordance with the relevant U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has shown tremendous restraint in the current conflict
and wants to defuse the tensions as early as possible, said
Sharif.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister expressed his disappointment over the
failure of the talks between Pakistani Foreign Minister Sartaj
Aziz and his Indian counterpart Jaswant Singh in New Delhi on June
12.
</P>
<P>
"The visit achieved nothing because India chose to adopt a
rigid position and imposed unilateral demands before even sitting
down to talk," Sharif noted.
</P>
<P>
"It has also escalated hostilities, thereby worsening the
situation on the LoC and undermining regional peace and security,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Sharif, who assumed office in February 1997, said he has been
keen to normalize relations with India with which Pakistan has a
long common boundary.
</P>
<P>
"My particular attention has been devoted to resolving all
outstanding issues, and more specially the Kashmir dispute which
has soured our relationship for the last 52 years," the prime
minister added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
