<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HIV Vaccine Set for Trial In Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Human safety trials on the
recently- developed AIDS vaccine will begin in Kenya from next
April, a local researcher has revealed.
</P>
<P>
Omu Anzala, an immunologist at the University of Nairobi, said
here Friday that phase one of the trials will begin after
researchers receive preliminary results from a similar initiative
which starts in August at Oxford University, Britain.
</P>
<P>
The vaccine has been developed jointly by Oxford and Nairobi
universities through a study involving two groups of sex workers
based in Nairobi's Majengo slums, the Daily Nation newspaper
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The groups are: 45 sex workers who are resistant to contracting
AIDS and another 90 low-term non-progressers who do not have AIDS
although having the virus since 1980, Anzala said.
</P>
<P>
Anzala said about 80 volunteers who will meet "certain set-up
criteria" will be involved in both studies, which might last
seven years.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank recently announced that it was considering
putting about five billion U.S. dollars into a joint project with
major drug companies to help develop a low-cost AIDS vaccine for
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
According to Julius Meme, director of medical services under
the Kenyan Health Ministry, the latest estimates show that 13 to
14 percent of all adult Kenyans were HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
"This means that 1.9 million people are infected, including
700,000 children under the age of five," Meme said.
</P>
<P>
In mid June, Kenya Health Permanent Secretary Philemon Mwaisaka
said more than 200,000 Kenyans would die from AIDS before the end
of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990626.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Germans Abducted Off Somalia Northeastern Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Reports from the northeastern
region of Somalia said that four Germans have been abducted by
militiamen loyal to the Somali Salvation Democratic Front (SSDF)
faction two days ago.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports received through the VHF radios here
in Mogadishu, the Germans were caught off the Alula coasts, about
100 km southeast of the port town of Bossaso.
</P>
<P>
A group of the SSDF militiamen specialized in sea piracy have
attacked the unarmed yacht in which the Germans were travelling
in.
</P>
<P>
Businessmen in Bossaso town told Xinhua that the Germans and
their yacht are being held in a small coastal village called
BoliMog, about 40 km northeast of Bossaso town.
</P>
<P>
Unlike earlier cases, the German travelers are not accused of
trespassing into the exclusive water zones of Somalia or of
conducting illegal fishing. However, the businessmen who
contacted the militiamen holding the German nationals said the
gunmen have forwarded their demand of ransom exceeding 50,000 US
dollars for the safe release of the German.
</P>
<P>
The abductors have guaranteed the safety of the hostages and
proper feeding until they are released. The businessmen are taking
the matter to the nearest German diplomatic mission which is in
Djibouti for the handling of the situation.
</P>
<P>
It is not known how the Germans ended up in trying to pass
through the piracy-rich waters of Somalia's northeastern coasts.
But sources coming from the area said the German have traveled
from New Zealand to head probably for the Indian Ocean islands
before they were intercepted by the armed men in northeaster
Somalia now known as Puntland.
</P>
<P>
There is no official word as yet from the local authority of
Puntland over the abduction in their area of control. However,
it is widely known that in earlier times the local authorities
had merely played mediation roles because otherwise any attempt
of use of force would only endanger the life of the abducted
people.
</P>
<P>
The sea pirates in the northeast Somalia often snatch vessels
passing through their water zones. The vessels include both
foreign fishing vessels and civilian yachts as well as commercial
vessels. In both cases a huge ransom is paid for the release of
those vessels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
