<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Machine Identifies Fake Invoices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Institute of Automation under
the Chinese Academy of Sciences has developed a machine which can
tell if a value-added tax invoice is fake or not within five
seconds.
</P>
<P>
The machine, which has already been tested at the State
Administration of Taxation and the taxation department in Jinan,
capital of east China's Shandong Province, has achieved an
accuracy of 98 percent.
</P>
<P>
The machine can deal with about 13,000 invoices a day, and has
greatly improved the efficiency of the taxation departments.
</P>
<P>
No special training is needed to operate the machine.
</P>
<P>
Taxation departments can use connected terminals to handle
large numbers of invoices and collect relevant data, and then put
the information into a centralized data bank.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the invention has improved anti-counterfeiting
technology for the taxation departments and will also play a
positive role in combating forgery of bank checks and other kinds
of bills and notes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
