<HEADLINE> Peace Cannot be One-Sided: Vajpayee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- India's Caretaker Prime Minister
Atal Behari Vajpayee said Saturday that although India wanted
peace with Pakistan, it could not be one-sided.
</P>
<P>
"We want peace, but it cannot be one-sided," he said in Pune, a
city 1,400 km south of New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
Referring to "Pakistan-backed infiltrators" in Kargil sector of
Kashmir along the Indo-Pakistan border, he said: "Initially we
faced some difficulties, but the situation has been tackled. Our
brave soldiers are capturing one height after another."
</P>
<P>
According to another report reaching here, caretaker Defense
Minister George Fernandes Saturday denied that Army Chief Gen V.
P. Malik had suggested crossing the Line of Control (LOC) along
the Indo-Pakistan borders in the Kashmir area to pin down
"Pakistani intruders."
</P>
<P>
"At no point of time the Army chief had suggested crossing the
LOC... Decisions on such vital matters are taken by the Cabinet
Committee on Security and all the three services chiefs are
present there," he told newsmen at Patna airport 1,015 km
southeast of New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether he perceived the possibility of a full-fledged
war with Pakistan, he said: "At the moment we are engaged in a
limited fight... Indian forces are rapidly gaining control of the
area occupied by the intruders." 
</P>
</TEXT>
