<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sri Lankan Doctors' Strike Hampers Civil War Solution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The political solution to Sri
Lanka's long-running civil war has run into an unlikely block --
striking doctors who favor centralization instead of devolution.
</P>
<P>
The two-week-long strike masterminded by the Government Medical
Officers' Association (GMOA) has not only incurred public
condemnation, but also run counter to the devolution package
designed to end the drawn-out civil war, analysts here said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of patients have been turned away since June 14 at
state hospitals where only emergency services are maintained.
Routine operations are canceled and out-patient departments remain
shut.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka provides free health services to its citizens, but
the ongoing strike deny treatment to poor families who cannot
afford expensive treatment at private hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Anger has been mounting against the striking doctors,
especially following the authorities' confirmation that two
patients had died due to lack of medical care.
</P>
<P>
Doctors said they were being subjected to physical attack. At
least one car belonging to a doctor was set on fire near the
capital Colombo Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In the northwest of the country, fuel pump attendants refuse to
serve striking doctors whose vehicles are identified by a blue and
white cross on the windshield.
</P>
<P>
The strike has continued despite an order by a Sri Lankan court
suspending trade union action over demands that the government
should not decentralize health administration.
</P>
<P>
The GMOA alleged that political involvement in the health
sector will lead to favoritism which will affect the well-being of
the health services.
</P>
<P>
All appointments, transfers and other official matters are
currently decided by the central government's Public Service
Commission.
</P>
<P>
The authorities said that they have no power to agree to the
doctors' demands as it is a constitutional matter. The
decentralization of health service was envisaged in an amendment
to the constitution in 1987.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Nimal Siripala de Silva said that he could not
scrap moves to decentralize the health administration because the
issue was pending in court.
</P>
<P>
A regional chief minister has filed a court action demanding a
ruling that health services be managed by semi-autonomous
provincial councils established in 1988 which are aimed at ending
the civil war by devolving more powers to regional authorities
including areas with large Tamil concentration.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has been plagued by a civil war since 1983 between
the government and Tamil rebels who demand a separate Tamil
homeland in the north and east of the island nation.
</P>
<P>
The ruling People's Alliance government had proposed a
devolution package before the parliament but fell short of a
two-third majority to make it a law thanks to the uncooperative
main opposition United National Party.
</P>
<P>
Considering the worsening medical situation, the Sri Lankan
government finally took legal actions against the striking doctors
by issuing arrest warrants.
</P>
<P>
Colombo District Judge A.W. Salam Friday ordered the immediate
arrest of the 12 executive committee member of the GMOA, allegedly
for defying the court ruling Tuesday which ordered a halt to the
strike until July 6.
</P>
<P>
The GMOA Friday night requested an urgent meeting with
President Chandrika Kumaratunga to discuss the doctors' strike
issue.
</P>
<P>
It seems that the striking doctors will soon have an answer
given the intervention from the highest level, but innocent
patients hope for an early return to normalcy to relieve their
sufferings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990626.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
