<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yunnan Reports Decline in Number of Drug Users </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Yunnan Province in southwest China
has reportedly curbed an epidemic of drug use, as the number of
drug addicts has dropped to 45,000 at present, from 57,000 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The local anti-narcotics authorities attributed the achievement
to unceasing efforts to crack down heavily on drug trafficking,
while carrying out massive preventive education campaigns, and
establishing highly-efficient monitoring and rehabilitation
networks.
</P>
<P>
Long utilized as a major transportation channel by
international drug traffickers, Yunnan is China's front line in
the battle against narcotics; it also has the biggest number of
drug addicts in the country.
</P>
<P>
In the 1990-1998 period, the local police dealt with 47,000
drug cases, arrested 66,000 drug traffickers, and seized some ten
tons of opium, 27 tons of heroin and more than 1,300 tons of
chemical materials used in the making of narcotics, according to
the Yunnan Provincial Drug Control Committee.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, educational activities have been held to dissuade
locals, particularly young people, from using narcotics. Schools
throughout the province are providing students with special anti-
drug courses which have helped schools in neighboring Myanmar
create drug-free campuses.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan has established a surveillance system to monitor drug
users, as well as more than 90 drug rehabilitation centers to help
addicts to kick the habit.
</P>
<P>
Drug users who are undergoing rehabilitation are also
encouraged to recount their experiences as a warning to the
general public to avoid drugs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990626.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burrell Beats Jones in Women's Long Jump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Dawn Burrell beat world 100
meters champion Marion Jones in the women's long jump at the U.S.
athletics championships in Eugene, Oregon, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Burrell, younger sister of former 100 meters world record-
holder Leroy Burrell, soared 6.96 meters on her fifth attempt, and
Jones, the world's top-ranked women's jumper who slightly sprained
her right knee two weeks ago, could not regain the lead.
</P>
<P>
Jones still made the American world championships team with her
second-place finish of 6.78 meters.
</P>
<P>
Jones, who fouled once and passed twice to protect the knee,
said she still hoped to win four gold medals at August's world
championships in Seville, Spain.
</P>
<P>
The 33-year-old Dennis Mitchell scored a surprise win in the
men's 100 meters in a wind-aided 9.97 seconds. Brian Lewis and Tim
Montgomery both clocked 10.00 seconds to complete the American
100m team for world championships.
</P>
<P>
Two-time Olympic champion Gail Devers finished second with a
time of 10.97 seconds in the women's 100 meters behind Inger
Miller in 10.96.
</P>
<P>
Devers, was the 1992 and '96 Olympic champion who was running
her first final in more than a year. Angela Williams was third in
11.03 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Olympic champion Charles Austin easily won the men's high jump,
clearing 2.28 meters and U.S. record-holder Lance Deal dominated
the men's hammer with a throw of 80.35 meters.
</P>
<P>
Chris Huffins scored 8,350 points to win the decathlon. World
record-holder Dan O'Brien missed the competition because of injury.
Shelia Burrell won the heptathlon with 6,101 points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
