<DOCNO> XIE19990626.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Cities Face Huge Air Pollution Tasks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese cities face a huge task of
improving their heavily polluted air, despite some achievements in
recent years, a leading Chinese legislator said here today.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Chairman Zou Jiahua of the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress, China's top legislative body, made the
remark in his report on inspection of air pollution prevention law
enforcement in five major cities.
</P>
<P>
The inspections found some improvements in the air environment
of the five cities, namely, Beijing, Shanghai, Xi'an, Lanzhou and
Shenyang.
</P>
<P>
"The worsening of air pollution have been halted, and some
major pollution indices have started to fall," said the legislator.
</P>
<P>
However, the air quality in these and other Chinese cities is
still much worse than that of major foreign cities. "We still have
huge tasks ahead in our fight against air pollution," he said.
</P>
<P>
Of the world's 10 most polluted cities, seven of them are in
China, and Beijing ranks third, according to a 1998 report from
the World Health Organization.
</P>
<P>
Acid rain has affected over 30 percent of China's land, and
economic losses caused by environmental pollution reached 187.5
billion yuan (about 22.6 billion U.S. dollars)-worth in 1995,
which was about 3.27 percent of China's GDP for that year.
</P>
<P>
To combat air pollution, China must, first of all, raise
environmental awareness throughout society, and instill in the
people a sense of urgency, Zou said.
</P>
<P>
The country should develop and adopt advanced technologies,
readjust the energy structure and develop clean energy, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the current legislation concerning air
pollution should also be amended, so as to lay a solid legal basis
for environmental protection, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
