<HEADLINE> China to Give Economy More Fiscal Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- China plans to enhance and improve
its macro-economic tuning-up, and give more fiscal support to spur
economic growth, according to Finance Minister Xiang Huaicheng
here today.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the 10th meeting of the Ninth National People
's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee, the Chinese minister said
that in the second half of this year a more active fiscal policy
will be pursued.
</P>
<P>
More emphasis will be put on increasing fiscal input into the
economy, raising workers' incomes and readjusting tax policies, he
said.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the government will take measures to attract
more foreign investment, and encourage both exports and domestic
consumption, so as to prop up the economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the first five months of this year, China's total fiscal
revenues reached 415.78 billion yuan (about 50 billion U.S.
dollars), up 24.9 percent over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Expenditures reached 352.98 billion yuan, up 17 percent over
the same five months of last year, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate of revenues was higher than that of the overall
economy, thanks to several special factors, such as higher import
growth, Xiang said.
</P>
<P>
Yet he warned that revenue growth could slow down in the second
half of the year unless the country takes effective measures to
counter slack domestic demand, shrinking exports and weak capital
spending.
</P>
<P>
On the final fiscal accounting of last year, Xiang said that
the central government's revenues were 548.91 billion yuan, up 13.
6 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Its total expenditures were 644.71 billion yuan, up 19.6
percent compared to the previous year. The central government's
deficit is 95.8 billion yuan, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
