<HEADLINE> Cambodian PM Calls for Efforts to Fight Drug Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian Prime Minister Hun
Sen Saturday asked the people to make further efforts to combat
trafficking in drugs and drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen, also chief of the National Authority for Combating
Drug (NACD), said in a message to mark the international anti-drug
day that the whole people, especially the young generation, should
not get involved in the drugs.
</P>
<P>
"Our country's future will depend on you," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to NACD Deputy Secretary General Nguon Soeur, drug
abuse among the youngsters has become widespread in Phnom Penh and
some provinces.
</P>
<P>
"Please be happy with music not the drug," Hun Sen said.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time Cambodia is holding anti-drug activities
on International Day Against Drug Abuse and Illicit Trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen also appealed to the authorities concerned and the
whole people to join hands in combating drug trafficking and drug
abuse, and urged farmers to stop cultivating marijuana which he
said was criminal acts.
</P>
<P>
Just like other Asian countries, the main drugs in Cambodia
include heroin, amphetamine and marijuana, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Prostitutes and night club girls are enjoying using drugs such
as amphetamine and ecstasy," said Nguon Soeur, adding that 70
percent of prostitutes and night club girls now use the drugs,
compared with only 15 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Unofficial figures also showed that 26 offenders have been
arrested in Phnom Penh this year, including Vietnamese, U.S., Thai
and Singaporean citizens. The authorities also seized more than
5,000 kilograms of marijuana, 800 grams of heroin, 4,819
amphetamine tablets and more than 1,000 grams of opium. 
</P>
