<HEADLINE> Fujian Sets up Anti-Drug Education Base For Teenagers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Province of Fujian in east
China has established an anti-drug education base for the
teenagers in the provincial capital of Fuzhou, which formally
opened to the public today.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the base was aimed to teach the younger
generation to "cherish life and reject drugs", said a local
official at the base's unveiling ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The base will host permanent exhibitions on dangers and harms
of narcotics, as well as efforts made in society at large to fight
drugs. Teenagers visiting the base can also watch anti-drug movies
released by the local government in the form of video compact
discs.
</P>
<P>
The site of the anti-drug education base was a memorial hall
devoted to Lin Zexu, a famous Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) official
who launched a fierce, courageous battle against the opium
smuggling to China by the British colonists in the early 19th
century. Though he failed eventually, Lin has been cherished and
honored by the Chinese people over generations in the past 150-odd
years as one of their country's national heroes.
</P>
<P>
Due to their curiosity and ignorance, some Chinese teenagers
have fallen victim to drugs. A recent survey shows that most of
the nearly 20,000 registered drug addicts in Fujian are young
people under the age of 25. 
</P>
</TEXT>
