<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 09:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon not to Curb Anti-Israel Resistance: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss
said his government will not be pressured into curbing the
resistance against Israeli occupation in the wake of the bloodiest
Israeli strike against the country since 1996.
</P>
<P>
"Resistance is a legal phenomenon in any country whose
territories are occupied. This is why Lebanon has the right to
resist the Israelis on its own land," Hoss told a news conference
at the premier palace Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether Hezbollah, or Party of God, had been asked to
stop launching Katyusha rockets in return for a de-escalation on
the Israeli side, Hoss said "Hezbollah is aware of its
responsibilities and is acting accordingly."
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah is leading a guerrilla war to oust
Israeli forces out of the country.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 allegely to protect its north from Lebanese guerrillas'
cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday night, Hezbollah fired Katyusha rockets into
northern Israel to avenge the wounding of a Lebanese woman by
Israeli shelling in south Lebanon. Two Israelis were killed by the
rockets.
</P>
<P>
In return, Israel launched a 10-hour air blitz on Lebanon's
infrastructure, killing eight people, most of them firemen, and
wounding 64 others.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's power stations, major bridges and roads around
Beirut were destroyed in the heaviest offensive since the 1996
16-day Israeli operation against the country which killed at
least 240 people, most of them civilians.
</P>
<P>
Hoss said the Lebanese government would rely on the five-nation
monitoring group, which is scheduled to convene Monday, to tackle
the recent situation.
</P>
<P>
The group, comprising representatives from the United States,
France, Syria, Lebanon and Israel, was charged with overseeing the
implementation of the April 1996 truce agreement reached between
Israel and Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
Hoss said Beirut would seek the interference of the United
Nations Security Council only if there are no other means for
solutions.
</P>
<P>
"We don't expect much more than a resolution (from the U.N.),
and there is already one, which is Resolution 425," Hoss said. The
resolution adopted after Israeli first invasion of Lebanon, calls
for an unconditional Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon,
</P>
<P>
Israel has been attempting to alter the resolution for a
pullout on the condition that Beirut provides it with security
guarantee beforehand, a move flatly rejected by Lebanon and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Syria, a main power broker behind Lebanon, has been seeking to
achieve a full Israeli withdrawal which includes its Golan
Heights captured by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
