<HEADLINE> Jordan Control Farm Operations Over Fears of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Jordanian government has put
under state control operations of 91 poultry farms across the
desert kingdom which had imported fodder from Belgium, Holland
and France amid fears of contaminations of dioxin.
</P>
<P>
Sample of chickens, eggs and fodder had been sent to
internationally recognized laboratories abroad to check whether
they contain the carcinogenic dioxin or not, Jordan`s official
news agency Petra said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Agriculture Ministry also asked the
governments in Holland, Belgium and France to provide a list of
companies which used high concentrations dioxin in
exported-oriented fodder, Petra said.
</P>
<P>
Fears over dioxin-contamination poultry feeds have sparked bans
by countries across the world on the import of beef or poultry
feeds from Belgium and other European Union (EU) countries.
</P>
<P>
Carcinogenic dioxin is a dangerous chemical substance which
could cause cancer and other serious health problems to human
beings, experts said.
</P>
<P>
Jordan imports large quantities of beef and fodder from EU
countries each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
