<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Complete Privatization In Two Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe will complete its
privatization program by privatizing about 50 public enterprises
within two years.
</P>
<P>
Cephas Msipa, Minister of State for Enterprises and
Indigenization, said Friday at the 27th Zimbabwe National Chamber
of Commerce annual congress, " the speed at which the enterprises
would be privatized will largely depend on how quickly we get
recommendations from the companies and approval from the
government."
</P>
<P>
The minister was quoted Saturday by the Herald Daily as saying
that the privatization process would be carried out in view of the
current economic environment. At the moment indigenous people
cannot afford to raise the money required to acquire companies
that are being privatized because of punitive interest rates and
other economic factors.
</P>
<P>
The government has been criticised for slowing down the
privatization exercise, which started about two years ago. The
exercise is seen as the key to reducing the huge budget deficit as
well as opening opportunities to previously disadvantaged black
entrepreneurs, he said.
</P>
<P>
So far, the government has only privatized Dairiboard Zimbabwe
Limited, the Cotton Company, the Commercial Bank of Zimbabwe, the
Zimbabwe Reinsurance Company and several other companies under the
Zimbabwe Development Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the government has done a lot in privatizing
state enterprises, something which was not being appreciated.
</P>
<P>
He urged small and medium-size enterprises to take advantage of
the opportunities brought about by privatization exercise, saying
they could play a crucial role in the privatization exercise.
</P>
</TEXT>
