<HEADLINE> Kenya to Spend $1 Billion on Debt Servicing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Kenya will spend at least one
billion U.S. dollars, or about 40 percent of its
180-billion-shilling (about 2.5-billion- U.S. dollar) revenue to
service its debts this year, according to a Kenyan economic
researcher.
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard newspaper Saturday quoted Joseph
Kimura, director of the Institute of Policy Analysis and Research,
as saying that 80 percent of the service goes to domestic debts
and the remaining to foreign debts.
</P>
<P>
The east African country's overall debt stood at 479.2 billion
shillings (about 6.7 billion dollars) by the end of March,
representing 67.4 percent of its gross domestic product (GDP),
official statistics showed.
</P>
<P>
Of the total debt, domestic debt makes up 31.7 percent and
foreign debts 68.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The debts have posed a major obstacle to Kenya's economy, which
has been in a recession in recent years. 
</P>
