<HEADLINE> EDS-Details added Talks between DPRK, ROK Resume in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) and the Republic of Korea (ROK) resumed their vice-
ministerial talks in a Beijing hotel this morning after a three-
day suspension.
</P>
<P>
Yang Young-Sik, vice-minister of ROK National Unification, and
Pak Yong-Su, deputy director-general of the DPRK Committee for
Peaceful Reunification of the Fatherland, greeted each other and
shook hands as the talks began.
</P>
<P>
Yang in his opening remarks hailed the winning of a DPRK women
soccer team over a Danish team in the on-going Women's World Cup
held in the United States, saying that such a victory epitomizes "
the national spirit and style of the Korean people."
</P>
<P>
Provided similar efforts are made by the two sides in the talks,
"small brooks will be turned into a big river," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Pak acknowledged that it is "the common aspiration" of both
sides to conduct good talks and that the talks should "yield
outcome" so as to "live up to the longing of the entire nation."
</P>
<P>
On the issue concerning the reunion of separated families, a
topic that the ROK side has placed high on the agenda, Pak said "
there are many overlapping pending issues for the two sides, not
just the reunion of separated families," but all the issues should
be dealt with one by one."
</P>
<P>
According to sources, during the closed-doors talks that lasted
one hour and fifty minutes, the two sides expressed their
respective stance and discussed the issues concerning the recent
naval skirmish occurred in the Yellow Sea and the separated
families reunion.
</P>
<P>
The ROK side set forth a specific plan for the reunion of
separated families and prompted the DPRK to discuss the plan, one
source said.
</P>
<P>
According to a prior agreement reached by the two sides, the
reunion issue should be listed in the prior agenda for the talks.
"The DPRK side held a positive attitude to the agreement reached
earlier," he said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides has agreed to reopen their talks in Beijing on
the morning of July 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
