<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Flies to U.S. for Talks on Bilateral, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on
Saturday flew to Washington for a six-day visit, during which he
will discuss a number of issues with U.S. President Bill Clinton
and other senior officials.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak was accompanied by a high-ranking delegation, including
ministers of information, economy, chief of presidential cabinet,
and foreign minister and presidential political advisor already in
the U.S..
</P>
<P>
He is expected to discuss with U.S. officials the Middle East
peace process. Egyptian officials said Mubarak will expound
Egypt's position on the Arab-Israeli peace talks and reiterate the
importance of adhering to the land-for-peace principle.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian leader is also to deal with other regional and
international issues, including the Iraqi situation.
</P>
<P>
Also high on the agenda of Mubarak's U.S. trip is to seek
further promotion of bilateral economic and trade ties. He will
discuss with U.S. officials ways of expanding Egyptian export to
the U.S. and American investments in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak will visit France after his U.S. trip, the
pro-government Al Gomhuria newspaper reported on Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
