<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Expressway In East China Passes State Quality Appraisal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 26 (Xinhua) -- A new expressway in east China's
Zhejiang Province today passed a state quality appraisal and was
formally accepted by the Ministry of Communications after two and
a half years of trial operation.
</P>
<P>
The 145-km, four-lane Hangzhou-Ningbo Expressway, which links
the provincial capital of Hangzhou to Ningbo, a coastal port city,
was completed at the end of 1996 after four-year construction. It
cost a total of 3.86 billion yuan (about 480 million US dollars),
including a loan of 180 million US dollars from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Builders of the road say that it is the first expressway China
has ever built in a coastal region covered with a chessboarded
network of rivers. Such regions have a very soft ground base,
which makes road construction extremely difficult.
</P>
<P>
Managers of the expressway have earned good profits during the
period of trial operation. And they collected 390 million yuan in
tolls in 1997 and are expecting to earn 900 million yuan this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
