<DOCNO> XIE19990626.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Special Envoy Leaves E. Timor For Jakarta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Secretary
General's special envoy for East Timor, Jamsheed Marker, left
Dili, capital of East Timor, on Saturday for Jakarta after ending
a three-day visit to the territory.
</P>
<P>
"I believe the Indonesian government, the military and the
police have a good intention to settle the East Timor case through
the direct ballot, as stated in the May 5 agreement," Marker said
before boarding a commercial plane at Dili's Comoro airport.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed between Indonesia and Portugal on May
5, the U.N. will deploy civilian police advisers from several
countries to assist Indonesian police in maintaining law and
order. A key function will be the disarmament of rival factions
that are either for or against independence.
</P>
<P>
"The U.N. Assessment Mission in East Timor (UNAMET) is ready to
team up with all sides to achieve a just and peaceful solution for
East Timor," Marker was quoted by Antara News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Marker said officials he met in meetings both in Jakarta and in
East Timor had shown their commitment to a peaceful solution for
the former Portuguese colony.
</P>
<P>
After arriving in East Timor on Thursday, Marker met with East
Timor Governor Abilio Jose Osorio Soares, regional commander Col.
Tono Suratman and head of the regional police office Col. Timbul
Silaen.
</P>
<P>
He also visited Baucau, Liquica and Lospalos districts in East
Timor to inspect logistical supplies and to observe the security
situation in the run-up to August's direct ballot.
</P>
<P>
The August ballot will allow the territory's people to choose
whether their homeland should become an autonomous region within
Indonesia or totally independent.
</P>
<P>
According to Antara, a second group of 30 U.N. civilian
policemen arrived in Dili on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The newly-arrived U.N. personnel consist of three Argentinians,
a Swede, a Zimbabwean, six Filipinos, 15 Australians and four
Bangladeshis.
</P>
<P>
They are joining 41 unarmed U.N. civilian policemen and 70 U.N.
volunteers who have been dispatched to all regencies in East
Timor.
</P>
<P>
All the U.N. poll officers have been tasked to help Indonesian
policemen during the direct ballot.
</P>
<P>
The East Timor was integrated into Indonesia in 1976 in a move
never recognized by the U.N., which still considers Portugal as
the administering power of the territory.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, Indonesia announced that it would grant East
Timor independence if the people there rejected Indonesia's offer
of a wide-ranging autonomy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990626.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Plans Northern Wheat Bases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- China plans to allocate some 60
million yuan to develop 66,700 ha of high quality winter wheat
bases in northern provinces such as Hebei, Shandong and Henan,
according to Vice-Minister of Finance Zhang Youcai.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that "the establishment of the winter wheat
bases will facilitate efforts to improve the quality of Chinese
wheat."
</P>
<P>
China's current demand for high-quality winter wheat outstrips
supply and the country is forced to import 10 million tons of
wheat annually. Wheat accounts for 90 percent of China's grain
imports and 10 percent of worldwide wheat imports.
</P>
<P>
Plans for the next three years call for establishing wheat
production bases in the aforementioned provinces and developing a
comprehensive production, processing and quality control system.
</P>
<P>
Hebei, Henan and Shandong provinces turn out 55 million tons of
wheat, or 47 percent of the national total, annually.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that the production of high quality winter wheat
will be spread to neighboring areas bases and similar bases will
be developed in southern China if the initial project proves
successful. 
</P>
</TEXT>
