<HEADLINE> Special Olympics World Summer Games Begin Tomorrow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RALEIGH, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The nine-day 10th Special Olympics
World Summer Games will start Saturday in Raleigh, North Carolina,
as the preparations for the Games completed today.
</P>
<P>
The forthcoming games, sanctioned by the Special Olympics
International (SOI), will run to July 4, with the participation of
7,000 mentally retarded athletes and 2,000 trainers from more than
160 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
The Special Olympics features 19 sports including aquatics,
athletics, badminton, basketball, bocce, bowling, cycling,
equestrian, soccer, golf, gymnastics, powerlifting, roller skating,
sailing, softball, table tennis, handball, tennis and volleyball.
</P>
<P>
The competitions will be staged at venues in Raleigh and its
nearby towns of Durham, Chapel Hill and Cary.
</P>
<P>
The Special Olympics were founded in 1968 by Eunice Kennedy
Shriver, sister of former U.S. President John F. Kennedy. So far,
the SOI has staged nine Summer Special Olympics Games and six
winter versions.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 Games operates with a 35.5-million-dollar budget which
is funded by corporations including Coca-Cola Company, foundations,
service organizations, individual contributions and grants.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation arrived in the United States on June 18
with 58 athletes, including 38 men and 20 women, competing in such
disciplines such as soccer, basketball, athletics, swimming,
gymnastics and table tennis.
</P>
<P>
The China Special Olympics Committee, which was set up in 1985,
has sent athletes to three Special World Summer Games, and held
two national Olympic Games in 1987 and 1991. In the past 15 years,
a total of 15 Chinese cities and provinces have held 90 sports
games for mentally disabled people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
