<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW -- Some 150 Polish troops left for the Balkans on Friday
to take part in NATO's peacekeeping mission in Kosovo, according
to the Polish news agency.
</P>
<P>
The troops, which are the first batch of 800 Polish servicemen
to join NATO's Kosovo mission, will arrive in Macedonia first,
before entering Kosovo to implement peace in the U.S.-controlled
area. The 800 servicemen will depart for Kosovo in groups until
next Tuesday, according to battalion commander Roman Polko. (
Poland-Peacekeeping)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- The Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) and
the Republic of Korea (ROK) resumed their vice-ministerial talks
in a Beijing hotel Sunday after three days of suspension.
</P>
<P>
Yang Young-Sik, vice-minister of national unification of South
Korea, and Pak Yong-Su, vice-director-general of the DPRK
Committee for Peaceful Reunification of the Fatherland, greeted
each other as the talks began. The two sides held one and a half
hours of talks last Tuesday, in which they discussed a number of
issues including the reunion of separated families, the
implementation of an accord signed in 1991 on reconciliation,
mutual non-aggression and cooperation between the north and the
south, and the recent skirmishes involving the two navies in the
Yellow Sea. (China-DPRK-ROK-Talks)
</P>
<P>
