<HEADLINE> Cambodian Party Convenes Central Committee Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Cambodian People's Party
(CPP) Saturday started a two-day central committee meeting to
prepare itself for the challenges of the future.
</P>
<P>
This is the CPP's 25th session and the first one since the new
coalition government was formed last November, making the CPP the
main ruling party.
</P>
<P>
At the opening session, CPP Chairman Chea Sim, who doubles as
president of the Cambodian Senate, set the task of the session as
 to summarize the work of the CPP done in 1998 and set up a new
strategy for the party in the next period and to sum up the
experience of last July's election and further strengthen the
unity of the party for the preparation of the next election in
2003.
</P>
<P>
Chea Sim highly valued the last election and the achievements
made by the new government in the short period of time.
</P>
<P>
Chea Sim cited the three main achievements made in the foreign
affairs as the resumption of Cambodia's seat in the United
Nations, obtaining of more than expected sum of assistance at
donor Consultative Group meeting in Tokyo and full membership in
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Chea Sim reaffirmed that the CPP will
continue to support the political policy of the government to
maintain political stability, integrate Cambodia into the
international community and normalize the influx of foreign
assistance.
</P>
<P>
Chea Sim also set forth the CPP's position to further enhance
the cooperation with the FUNCINPEC party in order to achieve
greater success.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 members and delegates attended the opening
session and they included Prime Minister Hun Sen, who is also the
party's vice chairman, and some foreign diplomats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
