<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts to Serve China's Procurators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Striving to ensure judicial
fairness, the Chinese Supreme People's Procuratorate (SPP) Friday
set up an expert consultation committee to advise procurators,
according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The committee's 26 members, all of them China's leading experts
in specialties of law, economics, finance, securities and natural
sciences, are expected to discuss procuratorial issues and offer
advice on them. Issues may include major and complicated cases as
well as SPP-drafted judicial interpretations and major regulations.
</P>
<P>
They are also responsible for informing SPP personnel on
professional matters.
</P>
<P>
The practice was tried in local procuratorates before being
brought to the SPP.
</P>
<P>
It has played an important role in improving procurators' work,
said China's top procurator Han Zhubin at a meeting marking the
establishment of the committee.
</P>
<P>
The nation's procurators, when handling cases, are increasingly
faced with problems requiring professional knowledge because of
fast-paced social, economic and scientific developments.
</P>
<P>
Not only should the procurators work to improve their quality,
but they should also resort to professional resources in the
society, Han said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
