<HEADLINE> Latin America, EU Start Pre-Summit Meeting in Rio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, June 25 (Xinhua) -- High-ranking officials from
Latin America, the Caribbean and the European Union (EU) started
the first pre-summit meeting here Friday to look at the main
documents and topics on the summit agenda.
</P>
<P>
The main political document, "Declaration of Rio de Janeiro,"
is expected to be adopted by the two-day summit that concludes
next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Rio Summit is the first of its kind grouping leaders or
their representatives of 48 countries from the two continents --
33 from Latin America and the Caribbean, and 15 from the EU.
</P>
<P>
Latin America, particularly the Southern Common Market (
Mercosur), hopes to talk EU leaders into starting early talks on a
free trade area for elimination of trade barriers, especially
those against agricultural and livestock products of the Mercosur
and the EU.
</P>
<P>
EU foreign ministers announced at a meeting in Luxembourg on
June 21 that the free trade negotiations would start on July 1,
2001, at the latest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
