<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Army Has No Fuel to Start Tanks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Army has taken the bite
of the economic crisis as its Second Cavalry Division has no fuel
to get its 300 tanks started due to an 80-percent cut in its fuel
budget, the Bangkok Post said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Also suffering are the 200 horses of the division, which have
been short of feed, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Quoting Major General Chalermpol Busayakul, commander of the
division, which is assigned to protect Bangkok, the newspaper said
the division is struggling to maintain war readiness.
</P>
<P>
The division usually starts the tanks every other day, but now
only once a week.
</P>
<P>
"We start the engine to warm them up but hardly drive them,"
the commander was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The best way to save on maintenance cost is to strip the tanks
down, grease the parts and put them in store. However, the
commander said they would not do so for fear of unexpected
incidents.
</P>
<P>
The division also takes care of 200 horses used in royal
ceremonies but faces a 20-percent cut in the feed budget.
</P>
<P>
Almost half of the horses are too old for any active service.
But they have to be kept in service since the division lacks the
270,000 baht (7,300 U.S. dollars) needed to buy and ship a new
recruit from Australia or New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Cash problems have also affected the division's four Cobra
helicopters, of which only two can fly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
