<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Lawmakers Seek Punishment For False Accounts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese legislators are hoping
that mounting punishments against those who keep false accounts
will help retard the trend, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
During discussions of the 10th session of the National People's
Congress (NPC) Standing Committee, legislators expressed a
unanimous view that they support the State Council's proposed
amendments to the 14-year-old Accounting Law, the English
newspaper noted.
</P>
<P>
Many of the legislators also expressed the hope that the
punishments for keeping dishonest accounts could be more severe,
said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Keeping false accounts seriously distorts economic order,
undermines the basis for making macro-economic policies and helps
finance the corruption of officials, said the legislators.
</P>
<P>
"Because so many people are doing it, people get the impression
that making untruthful accounts is no big deal," Gao Yibin, an
official from the Accounting Department of the Ministry of Finance,
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
In May of 1998, the ministry began to seek ways to remedy the
problem. It set up a set of guidelines to strengthen the checks
and balances on accountants, modernize accounting procedures and
increase punishments. This plan was adopted by the State Council
in May and was presented to the NPC Standing Committee for
adoption as a law this month, said Gao.
</P>
<P>
However, the current Criminal Law, which states that only
activities defined as crimes by the law can be punished, did not
define concealing, destroying and making false accounts as crimes,
according to the China Daily.
</P>
<P>
To solve this dilemma, it said, the State Council has decided
to ask the NPC Standing Committee to adopt a draft resolution on
the punishment of false accounting as a complementary document to
the Criminal Law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
