<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Brazilian Banker Supports Common Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian central bank
President Arminio Fraga on Friday expressed optimism over the
possible introduction of a common currency for the Southern Common
Market (Mercosur).
</P>
<P>
At a seminar during the summit of Latin America, the Caribbean
and the European Union, the top banker admitted that obvious
obstacles exist in the short term for the creation of a regional
common currency for the bloc comprising Argentina, Brazil,
Paraguay and Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
"We do not plan to adopt the U.S. dollar as our common currency,
and Argentina and other countries do not want to adopt the real,
which seems to me to be an incompatibility in the short and medium
term," said Fraga.
</P>
<P>
He added that Mercosur member countries must learn from the
experience of the euro, the single currency of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Chile and Brazil are associate members to the Mercosur.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
