<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Rejects U.S. Military Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Costa Rican government Friday
rejected any possibility of setting up a U.S. military base or
base for anti-drug traffic fight in the country as negotiations
are underway on joint patrolling by Costa Rican and U.S. forces
against drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Constitutional Court reaffirmed the ban on
foreign ships armed with cannons in the country's national waters
without the approval of parliament.
</P>
<P>
The United States has been trying to get the Costa Rican
government nodding on establishing a U.S. military base in the
country. U.S. Army Southern Command Chief Gen. Charles Wilhelm has
reportedly expressed an interest in operating in the north of
Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rican Security Vice Minister Rogelio Ramos confirmed
Friday that Wilhelm had explored the possibility of using the
Liberia City airport, some 250 kilometers north of San Jose.
</P>
<P>
The government stated that "any action against drug trafficking
must respect our constitutional norms and be appropriate to the
uniqueness of a people who abolished its army half a century ago."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
