<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central America Has "Big Expectations" for Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Guatemala and Central America
have "big expectations" of the Latin America-EU summit to be held
next week, Guatemalan Foreign Minister Eduardo Stein said on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Guatemala City quoted Stein as saying that the
programs of cooperation of the EU with the subregion countries
will be "consolidated" during the June 28-29 summit in Rio de
Janeiro.
</P>
<P>
The summit "validates the political importance Latin America
and the EU give to their relations," Stein said, adding that with
the meeting of their leaders, a level of dialogue "never before
seen" will be established.
</P>
<P>
Stein said this first summit should result in "agreements that
will promote an economic and commercial integration between the
parts," and at the same time, give more emphasis to the political
aspects.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said that the summit between both regions
"is for us a privileged space which we expect to consolidate."
</P>
<P>
The EU, made up of 15 nations, is the main donor for Central
America, including Guatemala, a country that receives some 550
million dollars for several programs.
</P>
<P>
Part of the assistance, some 200 million dollars, is aimed at
backing up the Guatemala peace process, signed in 1996, and also
to finance a series of regional projects.
</P>
<P>
The EU is launching some 117 projects in Guatemala in social
and productive matters to reduce the poverty that affects at least
80 percent of the 11 million Guatemala residents.
</P>
<P>
Over 16 percent of Guatemalan exports goes to the European
Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
