<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Concludes Talks with Andean Countries on Tariff Preferences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Brazil and four Andean
nations concluded negotiations on a new rule of common tariff
preferences on Friday, the Brazilian Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Four of the five members of the Andean Community -- Colombia,
Ecuador, Peru and Venezuela -- participated in the talks while
Bolivia sent observers to Brazil.
</P>
<P>
One negotiator, who asked not to be identified, said that
Colombia and Venezuela still have some unsolved problems with
Brazil, mainly on steel and petrochemical products.
</P>
<P>
Brazil also needs to resolve differences with Peru and Chile on
issues of fishing and hand-made products, the negotiator said.
</P>
<P>
He added that all the problems are expected be solved before
next week, when presidents of the countries concerned gather in
Rio de Janeiro to take part in a summit of the Latin America, the
Caribbean and the European Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
