<DOCNO> XIE19990626.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Welcomes Scrutiny of WB Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese officials said Friday that
they welcome the scrutiny of its use of a controversial World Bank
loan whether by foreign politicians, journalists or bank officials.
</P>
<P>
 A Finance Ministry official in charge of administration of
World Bank projects told China Daily that observers will find that
the loan will help improve the lives of its beneficiaries in every
ethnic group involved.
</P>
<P>
The bank's 24-member Board of Executive Directors on Thursday
approved the China Western Poverty Reduction Project, which is
expected to benefit 1.7 million of the poorest people in China,
the bank said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The bank's biggest shareholder, the United States, and the
third biggest, Germany, voted against the project.
</P>
<P>
But they failed to block the 311 million US dollars project,
of which 160 million US dollars will be funded by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government and the board agreed that the so-called
Qinghai component, at the center of the controversy surrounding
the loan, will not be implemented until the board reviews an
independent inspection study of the project.
</P>
<P>
Before the executive board meeting, China's representative at
the World Bank pledged the Chinese government's full support for
the review.
</P>
<P>
"We are in favor of transparency. Transparency brings to light
facts and scorches rumors," the Chinese government said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Under the Qinghai component of the project, which would use 40
million US dollars in World Bank loans, 58,000 people from six
impoverished counties in eastern Qinghai Province would relocate
to relatively wealthier Dulan County in Haixi Mongolian and
Tibetan Autonomous Prefecture of west Qinghai, on a voluntary
basis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
