<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian PDI-P Leads in Vote Counting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian Democratic Party of
Struggle (PDI-P) led by Megawati Soekarnoputri has maintained its
lead over the other 47 parties in the vote counting Saturday by
obtaining 31.82 million votes.
</P>
<P>
According to unofficial results collected by the official
Antara News Agency from provincial chapters of the Indonesian
Election Committee (PPI), the PDI-P gathered 34.1 percent of the
votes counted by Saturday morning, followed by the ruling Golkar
Party 20.85 million votes (22.28 percent), National Awakening
Party (PKB) 12.45 million votes (13.35 percent), United
Development Party (PPP) 9.58 million votes (10.28 percent),
National Mandate Party (PAN) 6.42 million votes (6.89 percent),
Crescent Star Party (PBB) 1.76 million votes (1.89 percent),
Justice Party (PK) 1 million votes (1.17 percent) and Justice and
Unity Party (PKP) 940,147 votes (1.01 percent).
</P>
<P>
The data showed that by Saturday morning, 39 of 48 political
parties contesting the June 7 elections still got less than one
percent of the total votes.
</P>
<P>
A total of 93.2 million votes or 79.12 percent out of the 117.8
million registered votes have been counted so far.
</P>
<P>
PDI-P has so far been dominant in 11 provinces, namely North
Sumatera, South Sumatera, Bengkulu, Lampung, Jakarta, West Java,
Central Java, Yogyakarta, Bali, East Kalimantan and Central
Kalimantan.
</P>
<P>
Golkar meanwhile took the lead in 14 provinces, namely West
Sumatera, Riau, Jambi, West Nusa Tenggara, East Nusa Tenggara,
East Timor, South Kalimantan, West Kalimantan, North Sulawesi,
South Sulawesi, Central Sulawesi, Southeast Sulawesi, Maluku and
Irian Jaya.
</P>
<P>
PPP remained on the top in the provisional tally in Aceh and
PKB was leading in East Java.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile official data collected by the General Election
Commission (KPU), based on votes counted till Saturday morning
showed PDI-P in the lead with 22.6 million votes, followed by
Golkar (11.787 million), PKB (11 million), PPP (6.2 million) and
PAN (4.27 million).
</P>
<P>
KPU officials stressed that the results of the election will be
determined by the official data issued by KPU and other data are
unofficial.
</P>
<P>
Forty-eight political parties took part in the election last
week to compete for 462 of the 500 seats in the DPR. The remaining
38 seats are reserved for the military, whose members do not vote.
</P>
<P>
KPU officials said the KPU will announce the final results of
the elections on July 8. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
