<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Following are highlights of today'
s major Beijing-based newspapers.
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The renovation project of the Tiananmen Square in downtown
Beijing has completed, and the square will be reopened to the
public next Monday.
</P>
<P>
-- The number of overseas-funded enterprises in China had
exceeded 330,000 by the end of last May. These enterprises used
overseas capital worth a total of 281.356 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
-- Beijing has set up an automatic urban fire alarm and
control network, which connects the internal fire alarm systems of
all enterprises and carries out an around-the-clock supervision on
any possible fires anywhere in the city.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Li Ruihuan, chairman of the National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference, China's top
government advisory body, Friday underlined the importance of
promoting afforestation across the country.
</P>
<P>
China needs to further increase the people's awareness of
environmental protection and make tree-planting everyone's
obligation from generation to generation, said Li, also a member
of the Standing Committee of the Political Bureau of the Communist
Party of China's Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese top lawmaker Li Peng yesterday afternoon had a
meeting with Minister of Foreign Affairs and Cooperation of
Mauritania Ahmed Ould Sid'Ahmed and his party. Li, chairman of the
National People's Congress Standing Committee, also met with
Harkishan Singh Surjeet, general secretary of the Communist Party
of India (Marxist), and a delegation from the France-China Amity
Society of the French Senate led by the society's chairman Jean
Besson.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese legislators Friday deliberated a draft amendment to
the Law in Beijing on the Protection of the Ocean Environment,
calling for equal importance to be attached to ocean environmental
protection as to that of the land.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China is planning to invest as much as one billion yuan (
120 million US dollars) in technology-intensive small and medium
enterprises across the country, according to Deng Nan, vice-
minister of science and technology. The money, expected to be
disbursed among some 1,000 start-up firms, could result in the
creation of 100,000 new jobs.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese officials said Friday that they welcome scrutiny of
its use of a controversial World Bank loan whether by foreign
politicians, journalists or bank officials. The World Bank on
Thursday approved the China Western Poverty Reduction Project,
which is expected to benefit 1.7 million of the poorest people in
China with a World Bank loan of 160 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
-- Striving to ensure judicial fairness, the Supreme People's
Procuratorate Friday set up an expert consultation committee to
advise procurators. The committee's 26 members, all Chinese
leading experts in specialties of law, economics, finance,
securities and natural sciences, are expected to discuss
procuratorial issues and give advice on them.  
</P>
</TEXT>
