<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Render More Support to High-Tech Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- One billion yuan (120 million US
dollars) has been set aside for investment in technology-intensive
small and medium enterprises in China, the English newspaper China
Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The funds, expected to be disbursed among as many as 1,000
start-up firms, could result in the creation of 100,000 new jobs.
</P>
<P>
Deng Nan, vice-minister of Science and Technology, said that
state money, jointly managed by the Ministry of Finance and
Ministry of Science and Technology, will be used to help selected
firms in the next three years achieve breakthrough in
technological innovations valued, potentially, at as much as 10
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
"The State will set up similar funds in the future, because
supporting innovation in small and medium enterprises is a long-
term policy of the country," Deng said.
</P>
<P>
Small and medium technological enterprises began emerging in
China during the early 1980s. Most were self-financed, independent
operations responsible for their own profits and losses. Their
development has contributed to hastening the nation's economic
growth.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
