<HEADLINE> Courier Wins Marathon Match in Wimbledon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Jim Courier won a marathon match
that lasted nearly four hours, advancing to the fourth round of
the Wimbledon tournament on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Couier overcame two match points to beat Dutchman Sjeng
Schalken 7-6 (7-2), 3-6, 3-6, 7-5, 13-11, after outlasting Carlos
Moya in five sets in his previous match.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time for Courier to advance to the fourth
round since 1993 when he eventually lost the final to Pete Sampras.
</P>
<P>
The English soil again brought out the best in 29-year-old
Courier as he rejuvenated his career by two thrilling five-set
victories to help an underdog U.S. Davis Cup team beat England at
Birmingham in April.
</P>
<P>
"That's Jim's strongest quality -- his heart," Sampras said. "
He's going to lay it on the line and fight as hard as he can.
Today was the perfect example. It's good to see him playing well
again."
</P>
<P>
Schalken looked tired in the latter stages of the match. The 1.
90 meters Dutchman double-faulted twice in his final service game,
then hit a backhand long on break point to give Courier a 12-11
lead.
</P>
<P>
The overflow crowd roared as Courier closed out the victory at
love, then punctuated it by gleefully punching the air with his
fists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
