<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT June 26 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. State Department on Friday confirmed
that an American was arrested in the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) on a charge of "violations of law."
</P>
<P>
"The government of the DPRK has confirmed to Swedish
authorities that an American citizen was arrested on June 17,"
State Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The individual -- whose name was not mentioned -- "is being
investigated for alleged violations of law," he said. (US-DPRK-
American)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Headway was reportedly made in easing a deadlock in
the Northern Irish peace process during four hours of talks with
the province's main parties in Belfast on Friday.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Ministers Tony Blair his Irish counterpart Bertie
Ahern said all the parties to the stalled Good Friday agreement
had backed fundamental principles including guerrilla disarmament
by May 2000 and the creation of a power-sharing provincial cabinet.
(UK-N.Ireland)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations Security Council on Friday
expressed "deep concern" at the escalation of tensions in the
Israel-Lebanon border which has affected civilians and U.N.
personnel.
</P>
<P>
"The members of the Council call on both sides immediately to
cease all hostilities and respect the resolutions of the Security
Council," June Council President Gambia's Baboucarr-Blaise Jagne
said in a press statement. (UN-Israel-Lebanon)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- A Russian T-154 passenger plane landed at the
Belgrade airport on Friday and it took off for Moscow again the
same day, as the Yugoslav capital reopened its airport to
international flights.
</P>
<P>
The Aeroflot flight was the first after the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia resumed international flights on Friday, with a flight
to Moscow. (Yugoslavia-airport)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- The Yugoslav military announced on Friday the
closure of its war-time press center after it had completed the
war-time work.
</P>
<P>
An international press center will take over from the army
press center for the coverage of post-war reconstruction of the
Balkan country, the military command said on Friday. (Yugoslavia-
Press Center) 
</P>
</TEXT>
