<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhejiang Building China's Longest Undersea Optical Fiber Cable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The construction of China's
longest undersea optical fiber cable has started in the eastern
coastal province of Zhejiang, local authorities announced here
today.
</P>
<P>
The building of the cable, with a length of 99.3 km and at an
estimated cost of nearly 50 million yuan (6 million US dollars),
is intended to improve telecommunications in Zhoushan, an island
city in the East China Sea.
</P>
<P>
With an area of some 540 sq km, Zhoushan is China's fourth
largest island and Zhejiang's largest. The island's external
telecom service has long depended on microwave transmission, which
is quite unstable and lags far behind the needs of the local
residents.
</P>
<P>
The starting point of the new cable is Ningbo, a coastal port
city opposite to Zhoushan island. The whole project is scheduled
to be completed in late July this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
