<HEADLINE> Wreckage of Angolan Police Helicopter Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Some wreckage of the helicopter of
the Angolan national police force, which crashed in Angola's
northern Namibe Province, has been found, the Angolan government
said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
However, the whereabouts of the senior government officials on
board including Deputy Interior Minister Jeronimo Marcolino remain
unknown, the Interior Ministry said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
According to the press release, the search and rescue team has
found two seats, a piece of a baggage and a landing lamp from the
helicopter at the coast along the Bay of Tigres in the south of
Namibe.
</P>
<P>
The team comprising rescuers from the Army, Navy and Air Force
will go on searching, it added.
</P>
<P>
At the request of the Namibe provincial government, a team of
South African technicians is expected to leave Angolan capital
Luanda for the crashing site to help with the search and rescue
mission.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government has ruled out the possibility that the
helicopter might be downed by the rebel National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), as they have hardly found
any UNITA military activities in the area.
</P>
<P>
Also on board the helicopter were high-level officials
including Deputy Director of the Angolan Intelligence Agency
Baltazar Gourgel, Director of the State Prison Administration
Fernando Coelho da Cruz Sobrinho, Police Commander of Namibe
Province Antonio Victor Teixeira da Cunha and Commander of the
National Police Air Force Pedro Brito Cavita.
</P>
<P>
Benjamim Bimbi, a correspondent from the Angolan Public
Television, was also among the missing.
</P>
<P>
They were heading for Bentiaba City Tuesday to attend the 20th
anniversary of the founding of the Interior Ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
