<HEADLINE> U.N. Urged to Be Reformed for 21st Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The African Regional Hearing
on the Millennium Assembly Friday urged that the United Nations
should be reformed, strengthened and refocused so as to be
adequately equipped to meet the regional and global challenges of
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The call has brought to a close the two-day intensive
discussions in Ethiopian capital Addis Ababa, which was organized
by the U. N. Economic Commission for Africa (ECA) and the Office
of the Coordinator of the Millennium Assembly headquartered in New
York.
</P>
<P>
According to an ECA press release issued here, the hearing
recommended that the U.N. Security Council need to be reformed to
reflect as wide a geographical distribution as possible.
</P>
<P>
It also stressed the need for the U.N. to address the problem
of proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and the need to
develop a system for financing global programs through corporate
taxation which would empower the world body and at the same time
ensure its impartiality.
</P>
<P>
In his closing remarks, U.N. Assistant Secretary-General Miles
Stoby, who is coordinator of the Millennium Assembly process,
urged governmental participants to take some of the issues raised
here to the forthcoming summit of the Organization of African
Unity in Algeria.
</P>
<P>
The two-day hearing was the second in a series of five regional
hearings organized as part of the consultative process leading to
a Millennium Summit of Heads of State and Government to take place
in New York in September 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
