<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WWF Appeals to Save Mediterranean From Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Worldwide Fund for Nature (WWF)
Friday appealed to the tourism industry to safeguard the
Mediterranean Sea and its coast from the pollution and other
ills inflicted on it by holiday-makers.
</P>
<P>
"Tourism is a double-edged blade," said WWF-Italy Chairman
Fulco Pratesi adding that "it is in danger of destroying our sea,
but it could also be decisive for its conservation if we choose
the path of sustainability."
</P>
<P>
The WWF estimates that this summer 165 million people will
visit beaches and resorts along the Mediterranean coastline.
</P>
<P>
One of the biggest problems is the strain these visitors put on
local water supplies. "Mediterranean tourists consume an average
of 300-350 liters of water a day if you count showers, swimming
pools and so forth," says Grazia Francescato of WWF International.
</P>
<P>
She adds that this figure is clearly excessive when you
consider that within a few years experts says 35 percent of the
Mediterranean population will have water supply problems.
</P>
<P>
The WWF is launching a campaign this summer to ask hotels and
restaurants all around the Mediterranean rim to cut wastage of
water.
</P>
<P>
It suggests a series of measures such as installing flush
regulators on toilets and only using dishwashers with full loads.
</P>
<P>
It also wants hotels and other tourist facilities to use less
polluting detergents when cleaning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
