<HEADLINE> Belgrade Reopens Airport to Intern'l Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 25 (Xinhua) -- A Russian T-154 passenger plane
landed at the Belgrade airport on Friday and it took off for
Moscow again the same day, as the Yugoslav capital reopened its
airport to international flights.
</P>
<P>
The Aeroflot flight was the first after the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia resumed international flights on Friday, with a flight
to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav national flag carrier JAT resumed its
Belgrade-Moscow-Belgrade flights three times a week until mid-July
while the Aeroflot would fly Moscow-Belgrade-Moscow flights four
times a week.
</P>
<P>
JAT has planned to introduce two more flights for a week after
mid-July.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav airlines, however, were not yet given permission
by European Union countries to land their flights in those
countries. The EU countries banned JAT flights last year after
they decided to tighten sanctions against the Balkan nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
