<DOCNO> XIE19990626.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC States Urged to Map Out Common Mining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Vice-President
Omar Ali Juma Friday called on the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) to map out a common strategy to fully utilize the
enormous potential in the mining industry.
</P>
<P>
Opening a meeting of SADC mining ministers in the northern
Tanzanian town of Arusha, Juma said it is necessary for the 14
members of the regional group to "maximize mining resources and
meet global changes."
</P>
<P>
He told the ministers that the mining industry is crucial to
the economy of the SADC countries as it contributes to some 10
percent of the gross domestic product (GDP) in the region.
</P>
<P>
"It is obviously a sector which cannot be ignored," reports
reaching here quoted Juma as saying.
</P>
<P>
Twelve ministers responsible for mining attended the meeting.
Ministers from South Africa and Malawi were absent because of the
elections in their countries.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president also urged the SADC countries to
collectively solve problems in the industry, noting that it is of
vital importance for all member states to ratify the protocol of
cooperation in the mining sector signed in Blantyre, Malawi, some
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
So far only seven SADC member states have ratified it.
</P>
<P>
On small-scale mining, the Tanzanian leader said that numerous
problems including a state of disorder and lack of proper
equipment and technology need to be tackled, but the sector needs
support as it is a big source of employment.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian vice-president blasted environmental destruction
in mining, stating that environmental impact assessment should be
made before the launching of any new projects.
</P>
<P>
He said large-scale operators must invest in upgrading
equipment for the sake of mining safety, especially in avoiding
using of mercury and cyanide in recovery of gold. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
