<DOCNO> XIE19990626.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African President Awaits Advice on DRC Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 25 (Xinhua) -- South African President Thabo
Mbeki is waiting for advice from Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba on whether or not the planned regional summit on the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) would go ahead on Saturday in
Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
"The president is waiting for advice from President Chiluba and
not from government sources," South African Press Association
quoted Mbeki's aide Ronnie Mamoepa as saying in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
Mamoepa was responding to media reports from Lusaka that key
figures to the conflict -- presidents Jose Eduardo dos Santos of
Angola, Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe, Laurent Kabila of the DRC and
Mbeki -- might not attend the crucial summit.
</P>
<P>
The defense and foreign ministers of countries engaged in
initiatives to end the 10-month war between Kabila's government
and the Tutsi-led rebels, allegedly backed by Rwanda and Uganda,
were to start their meeting in Lusaka later on Friday to pave the
way for their leaders' summit on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Chiluba, southern African peace mediator for the
DRC, was expected to fly to Kinshasa on Friday to convince Kabila
to travel to Zambia for the summit.
</P>
<P>
It was also reported that presidents Daniel arap Moi of Kenya,
Yoweri Museveni of Uganda and Benjamin Mkapa of Tanzania were
expected in the Zambian capital Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Organization of African Unity Secretary-General Salim Ahmed
Salim arrived in Lusaka earlier Friday for the talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
