<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt to Support Zambian Farmers in Production: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Egypt is to start supporting over
400,000 small-scale farmers in Zambia to enable them grow grain
for export to the middle east.
</P>
<P>
A Egyptian delegation led by Sayed Soliman, Egyptian Consultant
for African Affairs and International Commerce, is currently in
Zambia to explore areas of investment.
</P>
<P>
Egypt wants to invest more in Zambia because it is a safe
destination for any investment, Soliman said when calling on
Zambian Minister of Agriculture, Food and Fisheries, Suresh Desai
here Friday, .
</P>
<P>
"Zambia has been stable since independence and we consider it
safe for our investment," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that Zambia has the potential to grow various
grain which can be exported and earn the country foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Desai said the Zambian government would ensure that
the Egyptian investment is safe.
</P>
<P>
The minister explained that his government would also put
measures in place to ensure that small-scale farmers who will
benefit from the Egyptian support pay back their loans on time.
</P>
<P>
Desai noted that small-scale farmers in Zambia have usually
defaulted on loan repayments, adding that this has to be stopped
if agriculture is to develop. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
