<DOCNO> XIE19990626.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Summit for Congo(K) Peace May Be Postponed: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The regional summit on peace in the
 Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) scheduled for Saturday in
Zambian capital Lusaka may take place Sunday, Zambian
Vice-President Christon Tembo said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Tembo said that the summit, at which a cease-fire agreement is
expected to be signed, will be delayed because consultation talks
are still going on here.
</P>
<P>
He said the preparation of the final documents for the summit
will be ready Saturday and some issues still need to be sorted
out.
</P>
<P>
Tembo said that the summit will only take place after the
documents are prepared first.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president confirmed that Zambian Foreign Minister Keli
Walubita has gone to the DRC to consult President Laurent Kabila
on the regional summit.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, DRC representative attending the preparatory
meeting, Ngoyi Ngongo expressed satisfaction with the
preparations, saying that the preparations are going on well.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed the report that Kabila will not come for the
summit.
</P>
<P>
It is too early to say Kabila will not come because ministers
are still working for the summit, said Ngongo.
</P>
<P>
A representative of the rebel Congolese Rally for Democracy
(RCD) has arrived here for the summit.
</P>
<P>
Namibian Defense Minister Erikki Nghimtina said here Friday
that his country will pull its troops out of the DRC after the
cease-fire agreement is signed at the Lusaka summit.
</P>
<P>
Nghimtina arrived here Friday to attend the ministerial meeting
to make preparations for the summit.
</P>
<P>
Namibia, together with Angola, Zimbabwe and Chad, sent troops
to the third largest African country to back Kabila after the
rebel allegedly backed by Rwanda and Uganda took up arms against
Kabila early last August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
